[{"sha":"e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Update package.json versions as part of build step (#20579)

Fixes issue in the new build workflow where the experimental packages do
not include "experimental" in the version string. This was because the
previous approach relied on the RELEASE_CHANNEL environment variable,
which we are no longer setting in the outer CI job, since we use the
same job to build both channels. To solve, I moved the version
post-processing into the build script itself.

Only affects the new build workflow. Old workflow is unchanged.

Longer term, I would like to remove version numbers from the source
entirely, including the package.jsons. We should use a placeholder
instead; that's mostly how it already works, since the release script
swaps out the versions before we publish to stable.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JochLAin/react/commits/e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f"}]

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351599571
Change-Id: I1257887e869f891aa530212ea98540b86c02dc7d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Manas1820/tensorflow/commits/c79cce538184f10f4b635b3c9661821afdfc6881"},{"sha":"cd7b62464304f759b14928badd3663254e264bf4","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

[{"sha":"e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Update package.json versions as part of build step (#20579)

Fixes issue in the new build workflow where the experimental packages do
not include "experimental" in the version string. This was because the
previous approach relied on the RELEASE_CHANNEL environment variable,

same job to build both channels. To solve, I moved the version
post-processing into the build script itself.

Only affects the new build workflow. Old workflow is unchanged.

Longer term, I would like to remove version numbers from the source
entirely, including the package.jsons. We should use a placeholder
instead; that's mostly how it already works, since the release script

Change-Id: I63f1bdbfda99e20049dde682dfb65052779bf5e1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/5400e3e63cf1d3797ea4a42687e4b4f290a4cfaa"},{"sha":"febd380da9219e08ea493b5baff765e2ef2d99d5","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Do not hang in GPU tf.math.pow if RHS is a negative int.

Before, if the RHS to tf.math.pow in the GPU kernel was negative and the inputs were int64, the GPU kernel would hang. Eigen expects the RHS to be nonnegative and will go into an infinite loop otherwise. The CPU kernel already checks this and raises an error if the RHS is negative, but we cannot easily raise errors in GPU kernels.

For the C++ jax.jit, we were able to first perform the transfer, and then inspect the result to know what the dtype and shape are.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 347920180
Change-Id: I39489cd522cc9495a5c76bb756880c223b252920","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yongtang/tensorflow/commits/35f10f3f27d33975a4739cc7ebde0f16982851be"},{"sha":"bcfd86d52e4d5980b3d53a0021473d15f5709077","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Always execute TF ops on the local host CPU while constant folding

Currently, the op is executed on local device based on the device attribute but this is not intended and is causing recursive call in case of on-demand compilation of an op.

The op will be executed on host CPU if we don't explicitly set device for the eager op and provide input tensors on the host CPU.

Also, setting placement policy to TFE_DEVICE_PLACEMENT_EXPLICIT so that other devices are not used if no kernel is available on CPU. This will provide consistent behavior in different environments.

I don't see any easy way to have unit test for this commit without having a custom binary with GPU device and using some op that has different behavior on CPU and GPU. We have end to end tests for this in compiler/tests directory.

Removed an existing test that seems to be passing even if we don't force local device which was the original motivation for the change.

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old

Change-Id: I63f1bdbfda99e20049dde682dfb65052779bf5e1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/icpm/tensorflow/commits/5400e3e63cf1d3797ea4a42687e4b4f290a4cfaa"},{"sha":"febd380da9219e08ea493b5baff765e2ef2d99d5","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Do not hang in GPU tf.math.pow if RHS is a negative int.

Before, if the RHS to tf.math.pow in the GPU kernel was negative and the inputs were int64, the GPU kernel would hang. Eigen expects the RHS to be nonnegative and will go into an infinite loop otherwise. The CPU kernel already checks this and raises an error if the RHS is negative, but we cannot easily raise errors in GPU kernels.

Change-Id: Ia474fa08b7e4d830c3d4a2f04bd1cb6cda83736d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/icpm/tensorflow/commits/febd380da9219e08ea493b5baff765e2ef2d99d5"},{"sha":"6981355bc1fc9119f22759ec26a4d6b0714e9767","author":{"name":"Jean-Baptiste Lespiau","email":"d3229a97a8a1a3969929b7309247ec1d345f5156@google.com"},"message":"Add a function to get the signature associated to an argument.

For the C++ jax.jit, we were able to first perform the transfer, and then inspect the result to know what the dtype and shape are.
However, for pmap, we don't necessarily know how to transfer the arguments, before having inspected the signature and retrieved the compiled executable & sharding_sec.

So for pmap, we will do explicitly the "abstractify" and the "shard_args/device_put" steps.

This pass is now handled by first:
1. Decomposing control flow into the host and device portions first.
2. Moving all outside compilation ops to run in a single host parallel_execute region.

This simplifies the flow greatly and leads to simpler code path.  It will also allow the use of tf_device::LaunchOp to represent outside compilation regions.

[{"sha":"e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Update package.json versions as part of build step (#20579)

Fixes issue in the new build workflow where the experimental packages do
not include "experimental" in the version string. This was because the
previous approach relied on the RELEASE_CHANNEL environment variable,
which we are no longer setting in the outer CI job, since we use the
same job to build both channels. To solve, I moved the version
post-processing into the build script itself.

Only affects the new build workflow. Old workflow is unchanged.

Longer term, I would like to remove version numbers from the source
entirely, including the package.jsons. We should use a placeholder
instead; that's mostly how it already works, since the release script
swaps out the versions before we publish to stable.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Jeffkeen7/react/commits/e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f"},{"sha":"fc07b070a09396e60126dd75641472f0c7504edf","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Retry with fresh otp if publish fails (#20582)

Currently, if publishing a package fails, the script crashes, and the
user must start it again from the beginning. Usually this happens
because the one-time password has timed out.

With this change, the user will be prompted for a fresh otp, and the
script will resume publishing.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Jeffkeen7/react/commits/fc07b070a09396e60126dd75641472f0c7504edf"}]

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351599314
Change-Id: Iec6fd0ba9ac66815fa4491d4659e57dcbec73732","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/a919ce09c981bed97c04dc7508f2b790bcdc7933"},{"sha":"c79cce538184f10f4b635b3c9661821afdfc6881","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Eliminate handling of tuples from CustomCallThunk.

- Change CustomCallThunk to accept a vector of allocation slices for operands
  and results and delegate tuple flattening to the thunk emitter.

  cannot be resolved at compile time. That can happen only in the presence of a tuple
  select operation which is not supported in XLA:GPU.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351599571
Change-Id: I1257887e869f891aa530212ea98540b86c02dc7d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/c79cce538184f10f4b635b3c9661821afdfc6881"},{"sha":"cd7b62464304f759b14928badd3663254e264bf4","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

[{"sha":"e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Update package.json versions as part of build step (#20579)

Fixes issue in the new build workflow where the experimental packages do
not include "experimental" in the version string. This was because the
previous approach relied on the RELEASE_CHANNEL environment variable,
which we are no longer setting in the outer CI job, since we use the
same job to build both channels. To solve, I moved the version
post-processing into the build script itself.

Only affects the new build workflow. Old workflow is unchanged.

Longer term, I would like to remove version numbers from the source
entirely, including the package.jsons. We should use a placeholder
instead; that's mostly how it already works, since the release script
swaps out the versions before we publish to stable.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rafsanulhasan/react/commits/e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f"}]

[{"sha":"fc07b070a09396e60126dd75641472f0c7504edf","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Retry with fresh otp if publish fails (#20582)

Currently, if publishing a package fails, the script crashes, and the
user must start it again from the beginning. Usually this happens
because the one-time password has timed out.

With this change, the user will be prompted for a fresh otp, and the
script will resume publishing.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/chojar/react/commits/fc07b070a09396e60126dd75641472f0c7504edf"}]

For normal provider installation we want to associate each provider with
a selected version number and find a suitable package for that version
that conforms to the official hashes for that release.

Those requirements are very onerous for a provider developer currently
testing a not-yet-released build, though. To allow for that case this new
CLI configuration feature allows overriding specific providers to refer
to give local filesystem directories.

Any provider overridden in this way is not subject to the usual
restrictions about selected versions or checksum conformance, and
activating an override won't cause any changes to the selections recorded
in the lock file because it's intended to be a temporary setting for one
developer only.

This is, in a sense, a spiritual successor of an old capability we had to
override specific plugins in the CLI configuration file. There were
some vestiges of that left in the main package and CLI config package
but nothing has actually been honoring them for several versions now and
so this commit removes them to avoid confusion with the new mechanism.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/afe1e4e9a1d4ef1b06bf96e9351f1a9e70f1029a"},{"sha":"f4b686b5f3db28f09d2561eb2aee3e1c3a9bf270","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26614 from hashicorp/jbardin/0.14-26606

If the provisioner configuration includes sensitive values, it's a
reasonable assumption that we should suppress its log output. Obvious
examples where this makes sense include echoing a secret to a file using
local-exec or remote-exec.

This commit adds tests for both logging output from provisioners with
non-sensitive configuration, and suppressing logs for provisioners with
sensitive values in configuration.

Note that we do not suppress logs if connection info contains sensitive
information, as provisioners should not be logging connection
information under any circumstances.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/47f8ed4cd62068332eca4d1903b7dfaf6064adc4"},{"sha":"2b485cd4284725396abe26b5ae0175659199e78a","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"website: Sensitive values in provisioner config","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/2b485cd4284725396abe26b5ae0175659199e78a"},{"sha":"a18415686b40d89406992d5d300dc02566a91c4c","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26630 from hashicorp/alisdair/sensitive-values-provisioners-014

The Legacy SDK cannot handle missing strings from objects in sets, and
will insert an empty string when planning the missing value. This
subverts the `couldHaveUnknownBlockPlaceholder` check, and causes
errors when `dynamic` is used with NestingSet blocks.

We don't have a separate codepath to handle the internals of
AssertObjectCompatible differently for the legacy SDK, but we can treat
empty strings as null strings within set objects to avoid the failed
assertions.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/060f8acc081c9be2ef5b2d0277742ea753615ee2"},{"sha":"527f3e654cfd2417410ae4bdeffecfa53d28ea7b","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26641 from hashicorp/jbardin/backport-26638

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351599571
Change-Id: I1257887e869f891aa530212ea98540b86c02dc7d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/testkevinbonz/tensorflow/commits/c79cce538184f10f4b635b3c9661821afdfc6881"},{"sha":"cd7b62464304f759b14928badd3663254e264bf4","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

Because the destroy plan only creates the necessary changes for apply to
remove all the resources, it does no reading of resources or data
sources, leading to stale data in the state. In most cases this is not a
problem, but when a provider configuration is using resource values, the
provider may not be able to run correctly during apply. In prior
versions of terraform, the implicit refresh that happened during
`terraform destroy` would update the data sources and remove missing
resources from state as required.

The destroy plan graph has a minimal amount of information, so it is not
feasible to work the reading of resources into the operation without
completely replicating the normal plan graph, and updating the plan
graph and all destroy node implementation is also a considerable amount
of refactoring. Instead, we can run a normal plan which is used to
refresh the state before creating the destroy plan. This brings back
similar behavior to core versions prior to 0.14, and the refresh can
still be skipped using the `-refresh=false` cli flag.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mahak/terraform/commits/0b3b84acc1ade2e394fcb7e3b956bf2ea0789eb1"},{"sha":"e614fb9aed597252e6ca18244ca779e0d61d3683","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"refresh is expected for destroy

[{"sha":"95eb4907805b0c8650cc1bce01844162c2c84c4a","author":{"name":"Eric Mountain","email":"7fc8ed40e23fcba13e771e5ff7913ff89a4ed835@datadoghq.com"},"message":"Use v2 capabilities in layer archives

When building images in a user-namespaced container, v3 capabilities are
stored including the root UID of the creator of the user-namespace.

This UID does not make sense outside the build environment however. If
the image is run in a non-user-namespaced runtime, or if a user-namespaced
runtime uses a different UID, the capabilities requested by the effective
bit will not be honoured by `execve(2)` due to this mismatch.

Instead, we convert v3 capabilities to v2, dropping the root UID on the
fly.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351599571
Change-Id: I1257887e869f891aa530212ea98540b86c02dc7d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/YINZHI-keji/tensorflow/commits/c79cce538184f10f4b635b3c9661821afdfc6881"},{"sha":"cd7b62464304f759b14928badd3663254e264bf4","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351620042
Change-Id: I6ea89b0879013b72ad00e1d607223059a482a630","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/dabf3d8057094da094b59cfe445d1c72c0a25317"},{"sha":"706350f02372cbed8ee9dae04aabbc4a5da84760","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Implement round-robin reads.

This enables a new mode of reading from the tf.data service, where consumers read from tasks in a coordinated fashion, instead of the normal first-come first-served.

The main use case for this is coordinated bucketization for synchronous training, where we want to ensure that at each step consumers get batches with elements of similar sizes. This mitigates the inefficiency of some consumers slowly training on large examples while others quickly train on small examples, then block waiting for the slower examples to be processed.

When `consumer_index` and `num_consumers` are specified to `distribute`, each task will enforce a strict round-robin order, where its first element goes to consumer 0, second element to consumer 1, and so on. This requires that all consumers consume the same number of elements.

[{"sha":"46dfc313421a2f59a82343d8b812de799b3a0251","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"integration: fix TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2 not using frozen image

Commit f2f5106c92fb9399844dcb7315fe23f3612e7cea added this test to verify loading
of images that were built with user-namespaces enabled.

However, because this test spins up a new daemon, not the daemon that's set up by
the test-suite's `TestMain()` (which loads the frozen images).

As a result, the `debian:bullseye` image was pulled from Docker Hub when running
the test;

    Calling POST /v1.41/images/load?quiet=1
    Applying tar in /go/src/github.com/docker/docker/bundles/test-integration/TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2/d4d366b15997b/root/165536.165536/overlay2/3f7f9375197667acaf7bc810b34689c21f8fed9c52c6765c032497092ca023d6/diff" storage-driver=overlay
    Applied tar sha256:845f0e5159140e9dbcad00c0326c2a506fbe375aa1c229c43f082867d283149c to 3f7f9375197667acaf7bc810b34689c21f8fed9c52c6765c032497092ca023d6, size: 5922359
    Calling POST /v1.41/build?buildargs=null&cachefrom=null&cgroupparent=&cpuperiod=0&cpuquota=0&cpusetcpus=&cpusetmems=&cpushares=0&dockerfile=&labels=null&memory=0&memswap=0&networkmode=&rm=0&shmsize=0&t=capabilities%3A1.0&target=&ulimits=null&version=
    Trying to pull debian from https://registry-1.docker.io v2
    Fetching manifest from remote" digest="sha256:f169dbadc9021fc0b08e371d50a772809286a167f62a8b6ae86e4745878d283d" error="<nil>" remote="docker.io/library/debian:bullseye
    Pulling ref from V2 registry: debian:bullseye
    ...

This patch updates `TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2` to load the
frozen image. `StartWithBusybox` is also changed to `Start`, because the test
is not using the busybox image, so there's no need to load it.

In a followup, we should probably add some utilities to make this easier to set up
(and to allow passing the list frozen images that we want to load, without having
to "hard-code" the image name to load).

[{"sha":"46dfc313421a2f59a82343d8b812de799b3a0251","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"integration: fix TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2 not using frozen image

Commit f2f5106c92fb9399844dcb7315fe23f3612e7cea added this test to verify loading
of images that were built with user-namespaces enabled.

However, because this test spins up a new daemon, not the daemon that's set up by
the test-suite's `TestMain()` (which loads the frozen images).

As a result, the `debian:bullseye` image was pulled from Docker Hub when running
the test;

    Calling POST /v1.41/images/load?quiet=1
    Applying tar in /go/src/github.com/docker/docker/bundles/test-integration/TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2/d4d366b15997b/root/165536.165536/overlay2/3f7f9375197667acaf7bc810b34689c21f8fed9c52c6765c032497092ca023d6/diff" storage-driver=overlay
    Applied tar sha256:845f0e5159140e9dbcad00c0326c2a506fbe375aa1c229c43f082867d283149c to 3f7f9375197667acaf7bc810b34689c21f8fed9c52c6765c032497092ca023d6, size: 5922359
    Calling POST /v1.41/build?buildargs=null&cachefrom=null&cgroupparent=&cpuperiod=0&cpuquota=0&cpusetcpus=&cpusetmems=&cpushares=0&dockerfile=&labels=null&memory=0&memswap=0&networkmode=&rm=0&shmsize=0&t=capabilities%3A1.0&target=&ulimits=null&version=
    Trying to pull debian from https://registry-1.docker.io v2
    Fetching manifest from remote" digest="sha256:f169dbadc9021fc0b08e371d50a772809286a167f62a8b6ae86e4745878d283d" error="<nil>" remote="docker.io/library/debian:bullseye
    Pulling ref from V2 registry: debian:bullseye
    ...

This patch updates `TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2` to load the
frozen image. `StartWithBusybox` is also changed to `Start`, because the test
is not using the busybox image, so there's no need to load it.

In a followup, we should probably add some utilities to make this easier to set up
(and to allow passing the list frozen images that we want to load, without having
to "hard-code" the image name to load).

post-processing into the build script itself.

[{"sha":"cd7b62464304f759b14928badd3663254e264bf4","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

[{"sha":"e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Update package.json versions as part of build step (#20579)

Fixes issue in the new build workflow where the experimental packages do
not include "experimental" in the version string. This was because the
previous approach relied on the RELEASE_CHANNEL environment variable,
which we are no longer setting in the outer CI job, since we use the
same job to build both channels. To solve, I moved the version
post-processing into the build script itself.

Only affects the new build workflow. Old workflow is unchanged.

Longer term, I would like to remove version numbers from the source
entirely, including the package.jsons. We should use a placeholder
instead; that's mostly how it already works, since the release script
swaps out the versions before we publish to stable.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/manojsdeveloper/react/commits/e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f"},{"sha":"fc07b070a09396e60126dd75641472f0c7504edf","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Retry with fresh otp if publish fails (#20582)

Currently, if publishing a package fails, the script crashes, and the
user must start it again from the beginning. Usually this happens
because the one-time password has timed out.

With this change, the user will be prompted for a fresh otp, and the
script will resume publishing.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/manojsdeveloper/react/commits/fc07b070a09396e60126dd75641472f0c7504edf"}]

Change-Id: I1257887e869f891aa530212ea98540b86c02dc7d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/c79cce538184f10f4b635b3c9661821afdfc6881"},{"sha":"cd7b62464304f759b14928badd3663254e264bf4","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

Change-Id: I63f1bdbfda99e20049dde682dfb65052779bf5e1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/huaxz1986/tensorflow/commits/5400e3e63cf1d3797ea4a42687e4b4f290a4cfaa"},{"sha":"febd380da9219e08ea493b5baff765e2ef2d99d5","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Do not hang in GPU tf.math.pow if RHS is a negative int.

Before, if the RHS to tf.math.pow in the GPU kernel was negative and the inputs were int64, the GPU kernel would hang. Eigen expects the RHS to be nonnegative and will go into an infinite loop otherwise. The CPU kernel already checks this and raises an error if the RHS is negative, but we cannot easily raise errors in GPU kernels.

Change-Id: Ia474fa08b7e4d830c3d4a2f04bd1cb6cda83736d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/huaxz1986/tensorflow/commits/febd380da9219e08ea493b5baff765e2ef2d99d5"},{"sha":"6981355bc1fc9119f22759ec26a4d6b0714e9767","author":{"name":"Jean-Baptiste Lespiau","email":"d3229a97a8a1a3969929b7309247ec1d345f5156@google.com"},"message":"Add a function to get the signature associated to an argument.

For the C++ jax.jit, we were able to first perform the transfer, and then inspect the result to know what the dtype and shape are.
However, for pmap, we don't necessarily know how to transfer the arguments, before having inspected the signature and retrieved the compiled executable & sharding_sec.

So for pmap, we will do explicitly the "abstractify" and the "shard_args/device_put" steps.

Before, if the RHS to tf.math.pow in the GPU kernel was negative and the inputs were int64, the GPU kernel would hang. Eigen expects the RHS to be nonnegative and will go into an infinite loop otherwise. The CPU kernel already checks this and raises an error if the RHS is negative, but we cannot easily raise errors in GPU kernels.

[{"sha":"95eb4907805b0c8650cc1bce01844162c2c84c4a","author":{"name":"Eric Mountain","email":"7fc8ed40e23fcba13e771e5ff7913ff89a4ed835@datadoghq.com"},"message":"Use v2 capabilities in layer archives

When building images in a user-namespaced container, v3 capabilities are
stored including the root UID of the creator of the user-namespace.

This UID does not make sense outside the build environment however. If
the image is run in a non-user-namespaced runtime, or if a user-namespaced
runtime uses a different UID, the capabilities requested by the effective
bit will not be honoured by `execve(2)` due to this mismatch.

Instead, we convert v3 capabilities to v2, dropping the root UID on the
fly.

Signed-off-by: Eric Mountain <eric.mountain@datadoghq.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bergwolf/moby/commits/95eb4907805b0c8650cc1bce01844162c2c84c4a"},{"sha":"327daef5c19209898f11380a7bd02509d6675bcb","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"Merge pull request #41724 from EricMountain/dishonoured-capabilities

[{"sha":"8f556acfa1a6e58a0a59132469cca185df962b89","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Do not round trip to MLIR in the MLIR bridge if no TPUs are found

Currently, the filtering in the `IsEnabled` method doesn't inspect the devices but at the time of execution MLIR passes are skipped if there are no TPUs. This results in the conversion to MLIR and then back to GraphDef. This roundtrip does functionalization of control flow v1 and some other mutations so it is not idempotent.

Doing checks in the `IsEnabled` method will skip the unnecessary roundtrip.

[{"sha":"95eb4907805b0c8650cc1bce01844162c2c84c4a","author":{"name":"Eric Mountain","email":"7fc8ed40e23fcba13e771e5ff7913ff89a4ed835@datadoghq.com"},"message":"Use v2 capabilities in layer archives

When building images in a user-namespaced container, v3 capabilities are
stored including the root UID of the creator of the user-namespace.

This UID does not make sense outside the build environment however. If
the image is run in a non-user-namespaced runtime, or if a user-namespaced
runtime uses a different UID, the capabilities requested by the effective
bit will not be honoured by `execve(2)` due to this mismatch.

Instead, we convert v3 capabilities to v2, dropping the root UID on the
fly.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351620042
Change-Id: I6ea89b0879013b72ad00e1d607223059a482a630","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/dabf3d8057094da094b59cfe445d1c72c0a25317"},{"sha":"706350f02372cbed8ee9dae04aabbc4a5da84760","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Implement round-robin reads.

This enables a new mode of reading from the tf.data service, where consumers read from tasks in a coordinated fashion, instead of the normal first-come first-served.

The main use case for this is coordinated bucketization for synchronous training, where we want to ensure that at each step consumers get batches with elements of similar sizes. This mitigates the inefficiency of some consumers slowly training on large examples while others quickly train on small examples, then block waiting for the slower examples to be processed.

When `consumer_index` and `num_consumers` are specified to `distribute`, each task will enforce a strict round-robin order, where its first element goes to consumer 0, second element to consumer 1, and so on. This requires that all consumers consume the same number of elements.

[{"sha":"46dfc313421a2f59a82343d8b812de799b3a0251","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"integration: fix TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2 not using frozen image

Commit f2f5106c92fb9399844dcb7315fe23f3612e7cea added this test to verify loading
of images that were built with user-namespaces enabled.

However, because this test spins up a new daemon, not the daemon that's set up by
the test-suite's `TestMain()` (which loads the frozen images).

As a result, the `debian:bullseye` image was pulled from Docker Hub when running
the test;

    Calling POST /v1.41/images/load?quiet=1
    Applying tar in /go/src/github.com/docker/docker/bundles/test-integration/TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2/d4d366b15997b/root/165536.165536/overlay2/3f7f9375197667acaf7bc810b34689c21f8fed9c52c6765c032497092ca023d6/diff" storage-driver=overlay
    Applied tar sha256:845f0e5159140e9dbcad00c0326c2a506fbe375aa1c229c43f082867d283149c to 3f7f9375197667acaf7bc810b34689c21f8fed9c52c6765c032497092ca023d6, size: 5922359
    Calling POST /v1.41/build?buildargs=null&cachefrom=null&cgroupparent=&cpuperiod=0&cpuquota=0&cpusetcpus=&cpusetmems=&cpushares=0&dockerfile=&labels=null&memory=0&memswap=0&networkmode=&rm=0&shmsize=0&t=capabilities%3A1.0&target=&ulimits=null&version=
    Trying to pull debian from https://registry-1.docker.io v2
    Fetching manifest from remote" digest="sha256:f169dbadc9021fc0b08e371d50a772809286a167f62a8b6ae86e4745878d283d" error="<nil>" remote="docker.io/library/debian:bullseye
    Pulling ref from V2 registry: debian:bullseye
    ...

This patch updates `TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2` to load the
frozen image. `StartWithBusybox` is also changed to `Start`, because the test
is not using the busybox image, so there's no need to load it.

In a followup, we should probably add some utilities to make this easier to set up
(and to allow passing the list frozen images that we want to load, without having
to "hard-code" the image name to load).

[{"sha":"e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Update package.json versions as part of build step (#20579)

Fixes issue in the new build workflow where the experimental packages do
not include "experimental" in the version string. This was because the
previous approach relied on the RELEASE_CHANNEL environment variable,
which we are no longer setting in the outer CI job, since we use the
same job to build both channels. To solve, I moved the version
post-processing into the build script itself.

Only affects the new build workflow. Old workflow is unchanged.

Longer term, I would like to remove version numbers from the source
entirely, including the package.jsons. We should use a placeholder
instead; that's mostly how it already works, since the release script
swaps out the versions before we publish to stable.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/lancygoyal/react/commits/e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f"},{"sha":"fc07b070a09396e60126dd75641472f0c7504edf","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Retry with fresh otp if publish fails (#20582)

Currently, if publishing a package fails, the script crashes, and the
user must start it again from the beginning. Usually this happens
because the one-time password has timed out.

With this change, the user will be prompted for a fresh otp, and the
script will resume publishing.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/lancygoyal/react/commits/fc07b070a09396e60126dd75641472f0c7504edf"}]

previous approach relied on the RELEASE_CHANNEL environment variable,

post-processing into the build script itself.

[{"sha":"95eb4907805b0c8650cc1bce01844162c2c84c4a","author":{"name":"Eric Mountain","email":"7fc8ed40e23fcba13e771e5ff7913ff89a4ed835@datadoghq.com"},"message":"Use v2 capabilities in layer archives

When building images in a user-namespaced container, v3 capabilities are
stored including the root UID of the creator of the user-namespace.

This UID does not make sense outside the build environment however. If
the image is run in a non-user-namespaced runtime, or if a user-namespaced
runtime uses a different UID, the capabilities requested by the effective
bit will not be honoured by `execve(2)` due to this mismatch.

Instead, we convert v3 capabilities to v2, dropping the root UID on the
fly.

[{"sha":"46dfc313421a2f59a82343d8b812de799b3a0251","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"integration: fix TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2 not using frozen image

Commit f2f5106c92fb9399844dcb7315fe23f3612e7cea added this test to verify loading
of images that were built with user-namespaces enabled.

However, because this test spins up a new daemon, not the daemon that's set up by
the test-suite's `TestMain()` (which loads the frozen images).

As a result, the `debian:bullseye` image was pulled from Docker Hub when running
the test;

    Calling POST /v1.41/images/load?quiet=1
    Applying tar in /go/src/github.com/docker/docker/bundles/test-integration/TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2/d4d366b15997b/root/165536.165536/overlay2/3f7f9375197667acaf7bc810b34689c21f8fed9c52c6765c032497092ca023d6/diff" storage-driver=overlay
    Applied tar sha256:845f0e5159140e9dbcad00c0326c2a506fbe375aa1c229c43f082867d283149c to 3f7f9375197667acaf7bc810b34689c21f8fed9c52c6765c032497092ca023d6, size: 5922359
    Calling POST /v1.41/build?buildargs=null&cachefrom=null&cgroupparent=&cpuperiod=0&cpuquota=0&cpusetcpus=&cpusetmems=&cpushares=0&dockerfile=&labels=null&memory=0&memswap=0&networkmode=&rm=0&shmsize=0&t=capabilities%3A1.0&target=&ulimits=null&version=
    Trying to pull debian from https://registry-1.docker.io v2
    Fetching manifest from remote" digest="sha256:f169dbadc9021fc0b08e371d50a772809286a167f62a8b6ae86e4745878d283d" error="<nil>" remote="docker.io/library/debian:bullseye
    Pulling ref from V2 registry: debian:bullseye
    ...

This patch updates `TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2` to load the
frozen image. `StartWithBusybox` is also changed to `Start`, because the test
is not using the busybox image, so there's no need to load it.

In a followup, we should probably add some utilities to make this easier to set up
(and to allow passing the list frozen images that we want to load, without having
to "hard-code" the image name to load).

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

This enables a new mode of reading from the tf.data service, where consumers read from tasks in a coordinated fashion, instead of the normal first-come first-served.

The main use case for this is coordinated bucketization for synchronous training, where we want to ensure that at each step consumers get batches with elements of similar sizes. This mitigates the inefficiency of some consumers slowly training on large examples while others quickly train on small examples, then block waiting for the slower examples to be processed.

When `consumer_index` and `num_consumers` are specified to `distribute`, each task will enforce a strict round-robin order, where its first element goes to consumer 0, second element to consumer 1, and so on. This requires that all consumers consume the same number of elements.

This enables a new mode of reading from the tf.data service, where consumers read from tasks in a coordinated fashion, instead of the normal first-come first-served.

The main use case for this is coordinated bucketization for synchronous training, where we want to ensure that at each step consumers get batches with elements of similar sizes. This mitigates the inefficiency of some consumers slowly training on large examples while others quickly train on small examples, then block waiting for the slower examples to be processed.

Change-Id: I1257887e869f891aa530212ea98540b86c02dc7d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/isanjit3/tensorflow/commits/c79cce538184f10f4b635b3c9661821afdfc6881"},{"sha":"cd7b62464304f759b14928badd3663254e264bf4","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

reasonable assumption that we should suppress its log output. Obvious
examples where this makes sense include echoing a secret to a file using
local-exec or remote-exec.

non-sensitive configuration, and suppressing logs for provisioners with
sensitive values in configuration.

For normal provider installation we want to associate each provider with
a selected version number and find a suitable package for that version
that conforms to the official hashes for that release.

Those requirements are very onerous for a provider developer currently
testing a not-yet-released build, though. To allow for that case this new
CLI configuration feature allows overriding specific providers to refer
to give local filesystem directories.

Any provider overridden in this way is not subject to the usual
restrictions about selected versions or checksum conformance, and
activating an override won't cause any changes to the selections recorded
in the lock file because it's intended to be a temporary setting for one
developer only.

This is, in a sense, a spiritual successor of an old capability we had to
override specific plugins in the CLI configuration file. There were
some vestiges of that left in the main package and CLI config package
but nothing has actually been honoring them for several versions now and
so this commit removes them to avoid confusion with the new mechanism.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/30204ecded21fb52c992b0a707bb4cbb96e2c608"},{"sha":"d380f5873c5ba09b99860fba061200a6e27b3aaa","author":{"name":"Paul Thrasher","email":"d943e3484fefc8c5080ef9d8c0757459e55f3371@hashicorp.com"},"message":"Allow runs to continue on tfce error

[{"sha":"46dfc313421a2f59a82343d8b812de799b3a0251","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"integration: fix TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2 not using frozen image

Commit f2f5106c92fb9399844dcb7315fe23f3612e7cea added this test to verify loading
of images that were built with user-namespaces enabled.

However, because this test spins up a new daemon, not the daemon that's set up by
the test-suite's `TestMain()` (which loads the frozen images).

As a result, the `debian:bullseye` image was pulled from Docker Hub when running
the test;

    Calling POST /v1.41/images/load?quiet=1
    Applying tar in /go/src/github.com/docker/docker/bundles/test-integration/TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2/d4d366b15997b/root/165536.165536/overlay2/3f7f9375197667acaf7bc810b34689c21f8fed9c52c6765c032497092ca023d6/diff" storage-driver=overlay
    Applied tar sha256:845f0e5159140e9dbcad00c0326c2a506fbe375aa1c229c43f082867d283149c to 3f7f9375197667acaf7bc810b34689c21f8fed9c52c6765c032497092ca023d6, size: 5922359
    Calling POST /v1.41/build?buildargs=null&cachefrom=null&cgroupparent=&cpuperiod=0&cpuquota=0&cpusetcpus=&cpusetmems=&cpushares=0&dockerfile=&labels=null&memory=0&memswap=0&networkmode=&rm=0&shmsize=0&t=capabilities%3A1.0&target=&ulimits=null&version=
    Trying to pull debian from https://registry-1.docker.io v2
    Fetching manifest from remote" digest="sha256:f169dbadc9021fc0b08e371d50a772809286a167f62a8b6ae86e4745878d283d" error="<nil>" remote="docker.io/library/debian:bullseye
    Pulling ref from V2 registry: debian:bullseye
    ...

This patch updates `TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2` to load the
frozen image. `StartWithBusybox` is also changed to `Start`, because the test
is not using the busybox image, so there's no need to load it.

In a followup, we should probably add some utilities to make this easier to set up
(and to allow passing the list frozen images that we want to load, without having
to "hard-code" the image name to load).

[{"sha":"95eb4907805b0c8650cc1bce01844162c2c84c4a","author":{"name":"Eric Mountain","email":"7fc8ed40e23fcba13e771e5ff7913ff89a4ed835@datadoghq.com"},"message":"Use v2 capabilities in layer archives

When building images in a user-namespaced container, v3 capabilities are
stored including the root UID of the creator of the user-namespace.

This UID does not make sense outside the build environment however. If
the image is run in a non-user-namespaced runtime, or if a user-namespaced
runtime uses a different UID, the capabilities requested by the effective
bit will not be honoured by `execve(2)` due to this mismatch.

Instead, we convert v3 capabilities to v2, dropping the root UID on the
fly.

[{"sha":"eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command (#20573)

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rishi93/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"},{"sha":"9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate build tests to combined workflow (#20574)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rishi93/react/commits/9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374"},{"sha":"b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate remaining tests to combined workflow (#20577)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rishi93/react/commits/b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53"},{"sha":"e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Update package.json versions as part of build step (#20579)

Fixes issue in the new build workflow where the experimental packages do
not include "experimental" in the version string. This was because the
previous approach relied on the RELEASE_CHANNEL environment variable,
which we are no longer setting in the outer CI job, since we use the
same job to build both channels. To solve, I moved the version
post-processing into the build script itself.

Only affects the new build workflow. Old workflow is unchanged.

Longer term, I would like to remove version numbers from the source
entirely, including the package.jsons. We should use a placeholder
instead; that's mostly how it already works, since the release script
swaps out the versions before we publish to stable.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rishi93/react/commits/e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f"}]

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351599571
Change-Id: I1257887e869f891aa530212ea98540b86c02dc7d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/nkreeger/tensorflow/commits/c79cce538184f10f4b635b3c9661821afdfc6881"},{"sha":"cd7b62464304f759b14928badd3663254e264bf4","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

[{"sha":"46dfc313421a2f59a82343d8b812de799b3a0251","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"integration: fix TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2 not using frozen image

Commit f2f5106c92fb9399844dcb7315fe23f3612e7cea added this test to verify loading
of images that were built with user-namespaces enabled.

However, because this test spins up a new daemon, not the daemon that's set up by
the test-suite's `TestMain()` (which loads the frozen images).

As a result, the `debian:bullseye` image was pulled from Docker Hub when running
the test;

    Calling POST /v1.41/images/load?quiet=1
    Applying tar in /go/src/github.com/docker/docker/bundles/test-integration/TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2/d4d366b15997b/root/165536.165536/overlay2/3f7f9375197667acaf7bc810b34689c21f8fed9c52c6765c032497092ca023d6/diff" storage-driver=overlay
    Applied tar sha256:845f0e5159140e9dbcad00c0326c2a506fbe375aa1c229c43f082867d283149c to 3f7f9375197667acaf7bc810b34689c21f8fed9c52c6765c032497092ca023d6, size: 5922359
    Calling POST /v1.41/build?buildargs=null&cachefrom=null&cgroupparent=&cpuperiod=0&cpuquota=0&cpusetcpus=&cpusetmems=&cpushares=0&dockerfile=&labels=null&memory=0&memswap=0&networkmode=&rm=0&shmsize=0&t=capabilities%3A1.0&target=&ulimits=null&version=
    Trying to pull debian from https://registry-1.docker.io v2
    Fetching manifest from remote" digest="sha256:f169dbadc9021fc0b08e371d50a772809286a167f62a8b6ae86e4745878d283d" error="<nil>" remote="docker.io/library/debian:bullseye
    Pulling ref from V2 registry: debian:bullseye
    ...

This patch updates `TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2` to load the
frozen image. `StartWithBusybox` is also changed to `Start`, because the test
is not using the busybox image, so there's no need to load it.

In a followup, we should probably add some utilities to make this easier to set up
(and to allow passing the list frozen images that we want to load, without having
to "hard-code" the image name to load).

[{"sha":"706350f02372cbed8ee9dae04aabbc4a5da84760","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Implement round-robin reads.

This enables a new mode of reading from the tf.data service, where consumers read from tasks in a coordinated fashion, instead of the normal first-come first-served.

The main use case for this is coordinated bucketization for synchronous training, where we want to ensure that at each step consumers get batches with elements of similar sizes. This mitigates the inefficiency of some consumers slowly training on large examples while others quickly train on small examples, then block waiting for the slower examples to be processed.

When `consumer_index` and `num_consumers` are specified to `distribute`, each task will enforce a strict round-robin order, where its first element goes to consumer 0, second element to consumer 1, and so on. This requires that all consumers consume the same number of elements.

previous approach relied on the RELEASE_CHANNEL environment variable,

same job to build both channels. To solve, I moved the version
post-processing into the build script itself.

[{"sha":"95eb4907805b0c8650cc1bce01844162c2c84c4a","author":{"name":"Eric Mountain","email":"7fc8ed40e23fcba13e771e5ff7913ff89a4ed835@datadoghq.com"},"message":"Use v2 capabilities in layer archives

When building images in a user-namespaced container, v3 capabilities are
stored including the root UID of the creator of the user-namespace.

This UID does not make sense outside the build environment however. If
the image is run in a non-user-namespaced runtime, or if a user-namespaced
runtime uses a different UID, the capabilities requested by the effective
bit will not be honoured by `execve(2)` due to this mismatch.

Instead, we convert v3 capabilities to v2, dropping the root UID on the
fly.

[{"sha":"e3a5ec16905b5789bd32222c5fed0a2aea56486b","author":{"name":"Ken Franko","email":"99675e19a4e19629720cc97f93d3a35dad14ac72@google.com"},"message":"Rewrite TpuExtractOutsideCompilation pass without assuming clustering.

This pass is now handled by first:
1. Decomposing control flow into the host and device portions first.
2. Moving all outside compilation ops to run in a single host parallel_execute region.

This simplifies the flow greatly and leads to simpler code path.  It will also allow the use of tf_device::LaunchOp to represent outside compilation regions.

post-processing into the build script itself.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351620042
Change-Id: I6ea89b0879013b72ad00e1d607223059a482a630","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/dabf3d8057094da094b59cfe445d1c72c0a25317"},{"sha":"706350f02372cbed8ee9dae04aabbc4a5da84760","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Implement round-robin reads.

This enables a new mode of reading from the tf.data service, where consumers read from tasks in a coordinated fashion, instead of the normal first-come first-served.

The main use case for this is coordinated bucketization for synchronous training, where we want to ensure that at each step consumers get batches with elements of similar sizes. This mitigates the inefficiency of some consumers slowly training on large examples while others quickly train on small examples, then block waiting for the slower examples to be processed.

When `consumer_index` and `num_consumers` are specified to `distribute`, each task will enforce a strict round-robin order, where its first element goes to consumer 0, second element to consumer 1, and so on. This requires that all consumers consume the same number of elements.

[{"sha":"46dfc313421a2f59a82343d8b812de799b3a0251","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"integration: fix TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2 not using frozen image

Commit f2f5106c92fb9399844dcb7315fe23f3612e7cea added this test to verify loading
of images that were built with user-namespaces enabled.

However, because this test spins up a new daemon, not the daemon that's set up by
the test-suite's `TestMain()` (which loads the frozen images).

As a result, the `debian:bullseye` image was pulled from Docker Hub when running
the test;

    Calling POST /v1.41/images/load?quiet=1
    Applying tar in /go/src/github.com/docker/docker/bundles/test-integration/TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2/d4d366b15997b/root/165536.165536/overlay2/3f7f9375197667acaf7bc810b34689c21f8fed9c52c6765c032497092ca023d6/diff" storage-driver=overlay
    Applied tar sha256:845f0e5159140e9dbcad00c0326c2a506fbe375aa1c229c43f082867d283149c to 3f7f9375197667acaf7bc810b34689c21f8fed9c52c6765c032497092ca023d6, size: 5922359
    Calling POST /v1.41/build?buildargs=null&cachefrom=null&cgroupparent=&cpuperiod=0&cpuquota=0&cpusetcpus=&cpusetmems=&cpushares=0&dockerfile=&labels=null&memory=0&memswap=0&networkmode=&rm=0&shmsize=0&t=capabilities%3A1.0&target=&ulimits=null&version=
    Trying to pull debian from https://registry-1.docker.io v2
    Fetching manifest from remote" digest="sha256:f169dbadc9021fc0b08e371d50a772809286a167f62a8b6ae86e4745878d283d" error="<nil>" remote="docker.io/library/debian:bullseye
    Pulling ref from V2 registry: debian:bullseye
    ...

This patch updates `TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2` to load the
frozen image. `StartWithBusybox` is also changed to `Start`, because the test
is not using the busybox image, so there's no need to load it.

In a followup, we should probably add some utilities to make this easier to set up
(and to allow passing the list frozen images that we want to load, without having
to "hard-code" the image name to load).

Change-Id: I63f1bdbfda99e20049dde682dfb65052779bf5e1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/YINZHI-keji/tensorflow/commits/5400e3e63cf1d3797ea4a42687e4b4f290a4cfaa"},{"sha":"febd380da9219e08ea493b5baff765e2ef2d99d5","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Do not hang in GPU tf.math.pow if RHS is a negative int.

Before, if the RHS to tf.math.pow in the GPU kernel was negative and the inputs were int64, the GPU kernel would hang. Eigen expects the RHS to be nonnegative and will go into an infinite loop otherwise. The CPU kernel already checks this and raises an error if the RHS is negative, but we cannot easily raise errors in GPU kernels.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351461465
Change-Id: Ia474fa08b7e4d830c3d4a2f04bd1cb6cda83736d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/YINZHI-keji/tensorflow/commits/febd380da9219e08ea493b5baff765e2ef2d99d5"},{"sha":"6981355bc1fc9119f22759ec26a4d6b0714e9767","author":{"name":"Jean-Baptiste Lespiau","email":"d3229a97a8a1a3969929b7309247ec1d345f5156@google.com"},"message":"Add a function to get the signature associated to an argument.

For the C++ jax.jit, we were able to first perform the transfer, and then inspect the result to know what the dtype and shape are.
However, for pmap, we don't necessarily know how to transfer the arguments, before having inspected the signature and retrieved the compiled executable & sharding_sec.

So for pmap, we will do explicitly the "abstractify" and the "shard_args/device_put" steps.

[{"sha":"e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Update package.json versions as part of build step (#20579)

Fixes issue in the new build workflow where the experimental packages do
not include "experimental" in the version string. This was because the
previous approach relied on the RELEASE_CHANNEL environment variable,
which we are no longer setting in the outer CI job, since we use the
same job to build both channels. To solve, I moved the version
post-processing into the build script itself.

Only affects the new build workflow. Old workflow is unchanged.

Longer term, I would like to remove version numbers from the source
entirely, including the package.jsons. We should use a placeholder
instead; that's mostly how it already works, since the release script
swaps out the versions before we publish to stable.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JackEasons/react/commits/e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f"},{"sha":"fc07b070a09396e60126dd75641472f0c7504edf","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Retry with fresh otp if publish fails (#20582)

Currently, if publishing a package fails, the script crashes, and the
user must start it again from the beginning. Usually this happens
because the one-time password has timed out.

With this change, the user will be prompted for a fresh otp, and the
script will resume publishing.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JackEasons/react/commits/fc07b070a09396e60126dd75641472f0c7504edf"}]

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351620042
Change-Id: I6ea89b0879013b72ad00e1d607223059a482a630","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/tensorflow/commits/dabf3d8057094da094b59cfe445d1c72c0a25317"},{"sha":"706350f02372cbed8ee9dae04aabbc4a5da84760","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Implement round-robin reads.

This enables a new mode of reading from the tf.data service, where consumers read from tasks in a coordinated fashion, instead of the normal first-come first-served.

The main use case for this is coordinated bucketization for synchronous training, where we want to ensure that at each step consumers get batches with elements of similar sizes. This mitigates the inefficiency of some consumers slowly training on large examples while others quickly train on small examples, then block waiting for the slower examples to be processed.

When `consumer_index` and `num_consumers` are specified to `distribute`, each task will enforce a strict round-robin order, where its first element goes to consumer 0, second element to consumer 1, and so on. This requires that all consumers consume the same number of elements.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351599571
Change-Id: I1257887e869f891aa530212ea98540b86c02dc7d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/c79cce538184f10f4b635b3c9661821afdfc6881"},{"sha":"cd7b62464304f759b14928badd3663254e264bf4","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

Change-Id: I63f1bdbfda99e20049dde682dfb65052779bf5e1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Nicholas282787728/tensorflow/commits/5400e3e63cf1d3797ea4a42687e4b4f290a4cfaa"},{"sha":"febd380da9219e08ea493b5baff765e2ef2d99d5","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Do not hang in GPU tf.math.pow if RHS is a negative int.

Before, if the RHS to tf.math.pow in the GPU kernel was negative and the inputs were int64, the GPU kernel would hang. Eigen expects the RHS to be nonnegative and will go into an infinite loop otherwise. The CPU kernel already checks this and raises an error if the RHS is negative, but we cannot easily raise errors in GPU kernels.

For the C++ jax.jit, we were able to first perform the transfer, and then inspect the result to know what the dtype and shape are.
However, for pmap, we don't necessarily know how to transfer the arguments, before having inspected the signature and retrieved the compiled executable & sharding_sec.

So for pmap, we will do explicitly the "abstractify" and the "shard_args/device_put" steps.

[{"sha":"95eb4907805b0c8650cc1bce01844162c2c84c4a","author":{"name":"Eric Mountain","email":"7fc8ed40e23fcba13e771e5ff7913ff89a4ed835@datadoghq.com"},"message":"Use v2 capabilities in layer archives

When building images in a user-namespaced container, v3 capabilities are
stored including the root UID of the creator of the user-namespace.

This UID does not make sense outside the build environment however. If
the image is run in a non-user-namespaced runtime, or if a user-namespaced
runtime uses a different UID, the capabilities requested by the effective
bit will not be honoured by `execve(2)` due to this mismatch.

Instead, we convert v3 capabilities to v2, dropping the root UID on the
fly.

Signed-off-by: Eric Mountain <eric.mountain@datadoghq.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Skarlso/moby/commits/95eb4907805b0c8650cc1bce01844162c2c84c4a"},{"sha":"327daef5c19209898f11380a7bd02509d6675bcb","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"Merge pull request #41724 from EricMountain/dishonoured-capabilities

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351620042
Change-Id: I6ea89b0879013b72ad00e1d607223059a482a630","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/dabf3d8057094da094b59cfe445d1c72c0a25317"},{"sha":"706350f02372cbed8ee9dae04aabbc4a5da84760","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Implement round-robin reads.

This enables a new mode of reading from the tf.data service, where consumers read from tasks in a coordinated fashion, instead of the normal first-come first-served.

The main use case for this is coordinated bucketization for synchronous training, where we want to ensure that at each step consumers get batches with elements of similar sizes. This mitigates the inefficiency of some consumers slowly training on large examples while others quickly train on small examples, then block waiting for the slower examples to be processed.

When `consumer_index` and `num_consumers` are specified to `distribute`, each task will enforce a strict round-robin order, where its first element goes to consumer 0, second element to consumer 1, and so on. This requires that all consumers consume the same number of elements.

Change-Id: I63f1bdbfda99e20049dde682dfb65052779bf5e1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/5400e3e63cf1d3797ea4a42687e4b4f290a4cfaa"},{"sha":"febd380da9219e08ea493b5baff765e2ef2d99d5","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Do not hang in GPU tf.math.pow if RHS is a negative int.

Before, if the RHS to tf.math.pow in the GPU kernel was negative and the inputs were int64, the GPU kernel would hang. Eigen expects the RHS to be nonnegative and will go into an infinite loop otherwise. The CPU kernel already checks this and raises an error if the RHS is negative, but we cannot easily raise errors in GPU kernels.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351461465
Change-Id: Ia474fa08b7e4d830c3d4a2f04bd1cb6cda83736d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/febd380da9219e08ea493b5baff765e2ef2d99d5"},{"sha":"6981355bc1fc9119f22759ec26a4d6b0714e9767","author":{"name":"Jean-Baptiste Lespiau","email":"d3229a97a8a1a3969929b7309247ec1d345f5156@google.com"},"message":"Add a function to get the signature associated to an argument.

For the C++ jax.jit, we were able to first perform the transfer, and then inspect the result to know what the dtype and shape are.
However, for pmap, we don't necessarily know how to transfer the arguments, before having inspected the signature and retrieved the compiled executable & sharding_sec.

So for pmap, we will do explicitly the "abstractify" and the "shard_args/device_put" steps.

Change-Id: I6cf14701c300b599b8479831977c5654f04344e0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/e8f5a369d74455f3ae142ebfdc6b29939209ac3b"},{"sha":"8f556acfa1a6e58a0a59132469cca185df962b89","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Do not round trip to MLIR in the MLIR bridge if no TPUs are found

Currently, the filtering in the `IsEnabled` method doesn't inspect the devices but at the time of execution MLIR passes are skipped if there are no TPUs. This results in the conversion to MLIR and then back to GraphDef. This roundtrip does functionalization of control flow v1 and some other mutations so it is not idempotent.

Doing checks in the `IsEnabled` method will skip the unnecessary roundtrip.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351456908
Change-Id: I63f1bdbfda99e20049dde682dfb65052779bf5e1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/5400e3e63cf1d3797ea4a42687e4b4f290a4cfaa"},{"sha":"febd380da9219e08ea493b5baff765e2ef2d99d5","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Do not hang in GPU tf.math.pow if RHS is a negative int.

Before, if the RHS to tf.math.pow in the GPU kernel was negative and the inputs were int64, the GPU kernel would hang. Eigen expects the RHS to be nonnegative and will go into an infinite loop otherwise. The CPU kernel already checks this and raises an error if the RHS is negative, but we cannot easily raise errors in GPU kernels.

Change-Id: Ia474fa08b7e4d830c3d4a2f04bd1cb6cda83736d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/febd380da9219e08ea493b5baff765e2ef2d99d5"},{"sha":"6981355bc1fc9119f22759ec26a4d6b0714e9767","author":{"name":"Jean-Baptiste Lespiau","email":"d3229a97a8a1a3969929b7309247ec1d345f5156@google.com"},"message":"Add a function to get the signature associated to an argument.

For the C++ jax.jit, we were able to first perform the transfer, and then inspect the result to know what the dtype and shape are.
However, for pmap, we don't necessarily know how to transfer the arguments, before having inspected the signature and retrieved the compiled executable & sharding_sec.

So for pmap, we will do explicitly the "abstractify" and the "shard_args/device_put" steps.

[{"sha":"c75b21aa8b3f8efe20ebab68e59011744d5be460","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command: Use the new terminal.Streams object

Here we propagate in the initialized terminal.Streams from package main,
and then onwards to backends running in CLI mode.

This also replaces our use of helper/wrappedstreams to determine whether
stdin is a terminal or a pipe. helper/wrappedstreams returns incorrect
file descriptors on Windows, causing StdinPiped to always return false on
that platform and thus causing one of the odd behaviors discussed in

Finally, this includes some wrappers around the ability to look up the
number of columns in the terminal in preparation for use elsewhere. These
wrappers deal with the fact that our unit tests typically won't populate
meta.Streams.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/c75b21aa8b3f8efe20ebab68e59011744d5be460"},{"sha":"afab8459997593cb500a927950e9a432d94f4a73","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"backend/local: Use terminal properties to tweak the plan output

We now require the output to accept UTF-8 and we can determine how wide
the terminal (if any) is, so here we begin to make use of that for the
"terraform plan" command.

The horizontal rule is now made of box drawing characters instead of
hyphens and fills the whole terminal width.

The paragraphs of text in the output are now also wrapped to fill the
terminal width, instead of the hard-wrapping we did before.

This is just a start down the road of making better use of the terminal
capabilities. Lots of other commands could benefit from updates like these
too.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/afab8459997593cb500a927950e9a432d94f4a73"},{"sha":"0e6c4159d24b61b7dcb9ee1e465631fb777255e4","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command/format: Use box drawing chars for rules in diagnostics

We were previously using some ASCII art to create some visual divisions
between parts of the diagnostic output. Now that we are requiring a UTF-8
terminal we can print out box drawing characters instead.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/0e6c4159d24b61b7dcb9ee1e465631fb777255e4"},{"sha":"e272c5db16a6d48bc225bdfd385c0df87a01d030","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command/format: Don't try to fill the last terminal column

In some terminal emulators, writing a character into the last column on a
row causes the terminal to immediately wrap to the beginning of the next
line, even if the very next character in the stream is a hard newline.
That can then lead to errant blank lines in the final output which make
it harder to navigate the visual hierarchy.

As a compromise to avoid this, we'll format our horizontal rules and
paragraphs to one column less than the terminal width. That does mean that
our horizontal rules won't _quite_ cover the whole terminal width, but
it seems like a good compromise in order to get consistent behavior across
a wider variety of terminal implementations.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/e272c5db16a6d48bc225bdfd385c0df87a01d030"}]

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351620042
Change-Id: I6ea89b0879013b72ad00e1d607223059a482a630","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Nicholas282787728/tensorflow/commits/dabf3d8057094da094b59cfe445d1c72c0a25317"},{"sha":"706350f02372cbed8ee9dae04aabbc4a5da84760","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Implement round-robin reads.

This enables a new mode of reading from the tf.data service, where consumers read from tasks in a coordinated fashion, instead of the normal first-come first-served.

The main use case for this is coordinated bucketization for synchronous training, where we want to ensure that at each step consumers get batches with elements of similar sizes. This mitigates the inefficiency of some consumers slowly training on large examples while others quickly train on small examples, then block waiting for the slower examples to be processed.

When `consumer_index` and `num_consumers` are specified to `distribute`, each task will enforce a strict round-robin order, where its first element goes to consumer 0, second element to consumer 1, and so on. This requires that all consumers consume the same number of elements.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351620042
Change-Id: I6ea89b0879013b72ad00e1d607223059a482a630","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/isanjit3/tensorflow/commits/dabf3d8057094da094b59cfe445d1c72c0a25317"},{"sha":"706350f02372cbed8ee9dae04aabbc4a5da84760","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Implement round-robin reads.

This enables a new mode of reading from the tf.data service, where consumers read from tasks in a coordinated fashion, instead of the normal first-come first-served.

The main use case for this is coordinated bucketization for synchronous training, where we want to ensure that at each step consumers get batches with elements of similar sizes. This mitigates the inefficiency of some consumers slowly training on large examples while others quickly train on small examples, then block waiting for the slower examples to be processed.

When `consumer_index` and `num_consumers` are specified to `distribute`, each task will enforce a strict round-robin order, where its first element goes to consumer 0, second element to consumer 1, and so on. This requires that all consumers consume the same number of elements.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351599571
Change-Id: I1257887e869f891aa530212ea98540b86c02dc7d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/c79cce538184f10f4b635b3c9661821afdfc6881"},{"sha":"cd7b62464304f759b14928badd3663254e264bf4","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.
