into feature-micro-add-op-depth-to-space-pr1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/c20ac67cb1f52fa9303221a402b0705260ace812"},{"sha":"706350f02372cbed8ee9dae04aabbc4a5da84760","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Implement round-robin reads.

This enables a new mode of reading from the tf.data service, where consumers read from tasks in a coordinated fashion, instead of the normal first-come first-served.

The main use case for this is coordinated bucketization for synchronous training, where we want to ensure that at each step consumers get batches with elements of similar sizes. This mitigates the inefficiency of some consumers slowly training on large examples while others quickly train on small examples, then block waiting for the slower examples to be processed.

When `consumer_index` and `num_consumers` are specified to `distribute`, each task will enforce a strict round-robin order, where its first element goes to consumer 0, second element to consumer 1, and so on. This requires that all consumers consume the same number of elements.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351599571
Change-Id: I1257887e869f891aa530212ea98540b86c02dc7d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/c79cce538184f10f4b635b3c9661821afdfc6881"},{"sha":"cd7b62464304f759b14928badd3663254e264bf4","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

[{"sha":"46dfc313421a2f59a82343d8b812de799b3a0251","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"integration: fix TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2 not using frozen image

Commit f2f5106c92fb9399844dcb7315fe23f3612e7cea added this test to verify loading
of images that were built with user-namespaces enabled.

However, because this test spins up a new daemon, not the daemon that's set up by
the test-suite's `TestMain()` (which loads the frozen images).

As a result, the `debian:bullseye` image was pulled from Docker Hub when running
the test;

    Calling POST /v1.41/images/load?quiet=1
    Applying tar in /go/src/github.com/docker/docker/bundles/test-integration/TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2/d4d366b15997b/root/165536.165536/overlay2/3f7f9375197667acaf7bc810b34689c21f8fed9c52c6765c032497092ca023d6/diff" storage-driver=overlay
    Applied tar sha256:845f0e5159140e9dbcad00c0326c2a506fbe375aa1c229c43f082867d283149c to 3f7f9375197667acaf7bc810b34689c21f8fed9c52c6765c032497092ca023d6, size: 5922359
    Calling POST /v1.41/build?buildargs=null&cachefrom=null&cgroupparent=&cpuperiod=0&cpuquota=0&cpusetcpus=&cpusetmems=&cpushares=0&dockerfile=&labels=null&memory=0&memswap=0&networkmode=&rm=0&shmsize=0&t=capabilities%3A1.0&target=&ulimits=null&version=
    Trying to pull debian from https://registry-1.docker.io v2
    Fetching manifest from remote" digest="sha256:f169dbadc9021fc0b08e371d50a772809286a167f62a8b6ae86e4745878d283d" error="<nil>" remote="docker.io/library/debian:bullseye
    Pulling ref from V2 registry: debian:bullseye
    ...

This patch updates `TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2` to load the
frozen image. `StartWithBusybox` is also changed to `Start`, because the test
is not using the busybox image, so there's no need to load it.

In a followup, we should probably add some utilities to make this easier to set up
(and to allow passing the list frozen images that we want to load, without having
to "hard-code" the image name to load).

[{"sha":"8684c6b2e95601542c6c5c006bde5dd50f589a50","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Migrate convolution thunk emission to MLIR

- Map MLIR LHLO Conv operations to ConvolutionThunk.
- Refactor GetGpuConvConfig() to take in a conv descriptor, so that the same function
  can be used to emit a thunk from XLA HLO and MLIR representations.
- Change XlaConvLayoutsToStreamExecutorLayouts() to check shape<->layout
  compatibility instead of layout equality, since some XLA layouts with unit dimensions
   are not preserved in XLA HLO Shape -> MLIR -> XLA HLO Shape path.
- Note that window reversal is not yet representable in HLO/LHLO, so fall back to
   XLA HLO based thunk emission for that case.

[{"sha":"46dfc313421a2f59a82343d8b812de799b3a0251","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"integration: fix TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2 not using frozen image

Commit f2f5106c92fb9399844dcb7315fe23f3612e7cea added this test to verify loading
of images that were built with user-namespaces enabled.

However, because this test spins up a new daemon, not the daemon that's set up by
the test-suite's `TestMain()` (which loads the frozen images).

As a result, the `debian:bullseye` image was pulled from Docker Hub when running
the test;

    Calling POST /v1.41/images/load?quiet=1
    Applying tar in /go/src/github.com/docker/docker/bundles/test-integration/TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2/d4d366b15997b/root/165536.165536/overlay2/3f7f9375197667acaf7bc810b34689c21f8fed9c52c6765c032497092ca023d6/diff" storage-driver=overlay
    Applied tar sha256:845f0e5159140e9dbcad00c0326c2a506fbe375aa1c229c43f082867d283149c to 3f7f9375197667acaf7bc810b34689c21f8fed9c52c6765c032497092ca023d6, size: 5922359
    Calling POST /v1.41/build?buildargs=null&cachefrom=null&cgroupparent=&cpuperiod=0&cpuquota=0&cpusetcpus=&cpusetmems=&cpushares=0&dockerfile=&labels=null&memory=0&memswap=0&networkmode=&rm=0&shmsize=0&t=capabilities%3A1.0&target=&ulimits=null&version=
    Trying to pull debian from https://registry-1.docker.io v2
    Fetching manifest from remote" digest="sha256:f169dbadc9021fc0b08e371d50a772809286a167f62a8b6ae86e4745878d283d" error="<nil>" remote="docker.io/library/debian:bullseye
    Pulling ref from V2 registry: debian:bullseye
    ...

This patch updates `TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2` to load the
frozen image. `StartWithBusybox` is also changed to `Start`, because the test
is not using the busybox image, so there's no need to load it.

In a followup, we should probably add some utilities to make this easier to set up
(and to allow passing the list frozen images that we want to load, without having
to "hard-code" the image name to load).

Fixes issue in the new build workflow where the experimental packages do
not include "experimental" in the version string. This was because the
previous approach relied on the RELEASE_CHANNEL environment variable,
which we are no longer setting in the outer CI job, since we use the
same job to build both channels. To solve, I moved the version
post-processing into the build script itself.

Only affects the new build workflow. Old workflow is unchanged.

Longer term, I would like to remove version numbers from the source
entirely, including the package.jsons. We should use a placeholder
instead; that's mostly how it already works, since the release script
swaps out the versions before we publish to stable.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/react/commits/e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f"}]

Before, if the RHS to tf.math.pow in the GPU kernel was negative and the inputs were int64, the GPU kernel would hang. Eigen expects the RHS to be nonnegative and will go into an infinite loop otherwise. The CPU kernel already checks this and raises an error if the RHS is negative, but we cannot easily raise errors in GPU kernels.

Change-Id: I63f1bdbfda99e20049dde682dfb65052779bf5e1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/tensorflow/commits/5400e3e63cf1d3797ea4a42687e4b4f290a4cfaa"},{"sha":"febd380da9219e08ea493b5baff765e2ef2d99d5","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Do not hang in GPU tf.math.pow if RHS is a negative int.

Before, if the RHS to tf.math.pow in the GPU kernel was negative and the inputs were int64, the GPU kernel would hang. Eigen expects the RHS to be nonnegative and will go into an infinite loop otherwise. The CPU kernel already checks this and raises an error if the RHS is negative, but we cannot easily raise errors in GPU kernels.

[{"sha":"e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Update package.json versions as part of build step (#20579)

Fixes issue in the new build workflow where the experimental packages do
not include "experimental" in the version string. This was because the
previous approach relied on the RELEASE_CHANNEL environment variable,
which we are no longer setting in the outer CI job, since we use the
same job to build both channels. To solve, I moved the version
post-processing into the build script itself.

Only affects the new build workflow. Old workflow is unchanged.

Longer term, I would like to remove version numbers from the source
entirely, including the package.jsons. We should use a placeholder
instead; that's mostly how it already works, since the release script
swaps out the versions before we publish to stable.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/CrazyForks/react/commits/e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f"},{"sha":"fc07b070a09396e60126dd75641472f0c7504edf","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Retry with fresh otp if publish fails (#20582)

Currently, if publishing a package fails, the script crashes, and the
user must start it again from the beginning. Usually this happens
because the one-time password has timed out.

With this change, the user will be prompted for a fresh otp, and the
script will resume publishing.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/CrazyForks/react/commits/fc07b070a09396e60126dd75641472f0c7504edf"}]

Change-Id: I63f1bdbfda99e20049dde682dfb65052779bf5e1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/5400e3e63cf1d3797ea4a42687e4b4f290a4cfaa"},{"sha":"febd380da9219e08ea493b5baff765e2ef2d99d5","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Do not hang in GPU tf.math.pow if RHS is a negative int.

Before, if the RHS to tf.math.pow in the GPU kernel was negative and the inputs were int64, the GPU kernel would hang. Eigen expects the RHS to be nonnegative and will go into an infinite loop otherwise. The CPU kernel already checks this and raises an error if the RHS is negative, but we cannot easily raise errors in GPU kernels.

For the C++ jax.jit, we were able to first perform the transfer, and then inspect the result to know what the dtype and shape are.
However, for pmap, we don't necessarily know how to transfer the arguments, before having inspected the signature and retrieved the compiled executable & sharding_sec.

So for pmap, we will do explicitly the "abstractify" and the "shard_args/device_put" steps.

Change-Id: I1257887e869f891aa530212ea98540b86c02dc7d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/tensorflow/commits/c79cce538184f10f4b635b3c9661821afdfc6881"},{"sha":"cd7b62464304f759b14928badd3663254e264bf4","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

[{"sha":"46dfc313421a2f59a82343d8b812de799b3a0251","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"integration: fix TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2 not using frozen image

Commit f2f5106c92fb9399844dcb7315fe23f3612e7cea added this test to verify loading
of images that were built with user-namespaces enabled.

However, because this test spins up a new daemon, not the daemon that's set up by
the test-suite's `TestMain()` (which loads the frozen images).

As a result, the `debian:bullseye` image was pulled from Docker Hub when running
the test;

    Calling POST /v1.41/images/load?quiet=1
    Applying tar in /go/src/github.com/docker/docker/bundles/test-integration/TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2/d4d366b15997b/root/165536.165536/overlay2/3f7f9375197667acaf7bc810b34689c21f8fed9c52c6765c032497092ca023d6/diff" storage-driver=overlay
    Applied tar sha256:845f0e5159140e9dbcad00c0326c2a506fbe375aa1c229c43f082867d283149c to 3f7f9375197667acaf7bc810b34689c21f8fed9c52c6765c032497092ca023d6, size: 5922359
    Calling POST /v1.41/build?buildargs=null&cachefrom=null&cgroupparent=&cpuperiod=0&cpuquota=0&cpusetcpus=&cpusetmems=&cpushares=0&dockerfile=&labels=null&memory=0&memswap=0&networkmode=&rm=0&shmsize=0&t=capabilities%3A1.0&target=&ulimits=null&version=
    Trying to pull debian from https://registry-1.docker.io v2
    Fetching manifest from remote" digest="sha256:f169dbadc9021fc0b08e371d50a772809286a167f62a8b6ae86e4745878d283d" error="<nil>" remote="docker.io/library/debian:bullseye
    Pulling ref from V2 registry: debian:bullseye
    ...

This patch updates `TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2` to load the
frozen image. `StartWithBusybox` is also changed to `Start`, because the test
is not using the busybox image, so there's no need to load it.

In a followup, we should probably add some utilities to make this easier to set up
(and to allow passing the list frozen images that we want to load, without having
to "hard-code" the image name to load).

If the provisioner configuration includes sensitive values, it's a
reasonable assumption that we should suppress its log output. Obvious
examples where this makes sense include echoing a secret to a file using
local-exec or remote-exec.

This commit adds tests for both logging output from provisioners with
non-sensitive configuration, and suppressing logs for provisioners with
sensitive values in configuration.

Note that we do not suppress logs if connection info contains sensitive
information, as provisioners should not be logging connection
information under any circumstances.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/4f53234d8cf6c9f964ac8bfa8bce3a624a119bf1"},{"sha":"e3804810a9c95fe590f6eb3807a12d86a0ecf76e","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Accept JSON encoded dynamic values from providers

More precise handling of lists and maps within sets for ProposedNewObject","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/98dc3990628bb94f5877cd04e1cf56851ba8a7bb"},{"sha":"30204ecded21fb52c992b0a707bb4cbb96e2c608","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command/cliconfig: Allow development overrides for providers

For normal provider installation we want to associate each provider with
a selected version number and find a suitable package for that version
that conforms to the official hashes for that release.

Those requirements are very onerous for a provider developer currently
testing a not-yet-released build, though. To allow for that case this new
CLI configuration feature allows overriding specific providers to refer
to give local filesystem directories.

Any provider overridden in this way is not subject to the usual
restrictions about selected versions or checksum conformance, and
activating an override won't cause any changes to the selections recorded
in the lock file because it's intended to be a temporary setting for one
developer only.

This is, in a sense, a spiritual successor of an old capability we had to
override specific plugins in the CLI configuration file. There were
some vestiges of that left in the main package and CLI config package
but nothing has actually been honoring them for several versions now and
so this commit removes them to avoid confusion with the new mechanism.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/30204ecded21fb52c992b0a707bb4cbb96e2c608"},{"sha":"d380f5873c5ba09b99860fba061200a6e27b3aaa","author":{"name":"Paul Thrasher","email":"d943e3484fefc8c5080ef9d8c0757459e55f3371@hashicorp.com"},"message":"Allow runs to continue on tfce error

Change-Id: I63f1bdbfda99e20049dde682dfb65052779bf5e1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/5400e3e63cf1d3797ea4a42687e4b4f290a4cfaa"},{"sha":"febd380da9219e08ea493b5baff765e2ef2d99d5","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Do not hang in GPU tf.math.pow if RHS is a negative int.

Before, if the RHS to tf.math.pow in the GPU kernel was negative and the inputs were int64, the GPU kernel would hang. Eigen expects the RHS to be nonnegative and will go into an infinite loop otherwise. The CPU kernel already checks this and raises an error if the RHS is negative, but we cannot easily raise errors in GPU kernels.

For the C++ jax.jit, we were able to first perform the transfer, and then inspect the result to know what the dtype and shape are.
However, for pmap, we don't necessarily know how to transfer the arguments, before having inspected the signature and retrieved the compiled executable & sharding_sec.

So for pmap, we will do explicitly the "abstractify" and the "shard_args/device_put" steps.

For normal provider installation we want to associate each provider with
a selected version number and find a suitable package for that version
that conforms to the official hashes for that release.

Those requirements are very onerous for a provider developer currently
testing a not-yet-released build, though. To allow for that case this new
CLI configuration feature allows overriding specific providers to refer
to give local filesystem directories.

Any provider overridden in this way is not subject to the usual
restrictions about selected versions or checksum conformance, and
activating an override won't cause any changes to the selections recorded
in the lock file because it's intended to be a temporary setting for one
developer only.

This is, in a sense, a spiritual successor of an old capability we had to
override specific plugins in the CLI configuration file. There were
some vestiges of that left in the main package and CLI config package
but nothing has actually been honoring them for several versions now and
so this commit removes them to avoid confusion with the new mechanism.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/afe1e4e9a1d4ef1b06bf96e9351f1a9e70f1029a"},{"sha":"f4b686b5f3db28f09d2561eb2aee3e1c3a9bf270","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26614 from hashicorp/jbardin/0.14-26606

If the provisioner configuration includes sensitive values, it's a
reasonable assumption that we should suppress its log output. Obvious
examples where this makes sense include echoing a secret to a file using
local-exec or remote-exec.

This commit adds tests for both logging output from provisioners with
non-sensitive configuration, and suppressing logs for provisioners with
sensitive values in configuration.

Note that we do not suppress logs if connection info contains sensitive
information, as provisioners should not be logging connection
information under any circumstances.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/47f8ed4cd62068332eca4d1903b7dfaf6064adc4"},{"sha":"2b485cd4284725396abe26b5ae0175659199e78a","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"website: Sensitive values in provisioner config","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/2b485cd4284725396abe26b5ae0175659199e78a"},{"sha":"a18415686b40d89406992d5d300dc02566a91c4c","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26630 from hashicorp/alisdair/sensitive-values-provisioners-014

Change-Id: I1257887e869f891aa530212ea98540b86c02dc7d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/c79cce538184f10f4b635b3c9661821afdfc6881"},{"sha":"cd7b62464304f759b14928badd3663254e264bf4","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351620042
Change-Id: I6ea89b0879013b72ad00e1d607223059a482a630","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/YINZHI-keji/tensorflow/commits/dabf3d8057094da094b59cfe445d1c72c0a25317"},{"sha":"706350f02372cbed8ee9dae04aabbc4a5da84760","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Implement round-robin reads.

This enables a new mode of reading from the tf.data service, where consumers read from tasks in a coordinated fashion, instead of the normal first-come first-served.

The main use case for this is coordinated bucketization for synchronous training, where we want to ensure that at each step consumers get batches with elements of similar sizes. This mitigates the inefficiency of some consumers slowly training on large examples while others quickly train on small examples, then block waiting for the slower examples to be processed.

When `consumer_index` and `num_consumers` are specified to `distribute`, each task will enforce a strict round-robin order, where its first element goes to consumer 0, second element to consumer 1, and so on. This requires that all consumers consume the same number of elements.

[{"sha":"17728c8fe8f86bfe5e92cdfa4d2467279beb437f","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"internal/terminal: Interrogate and initialize the terminal, if any

This is a helper package that creates a very thin abstraction over
terminal setup, with the main goal being to deal with all of the extra
setup we need to do in order to get a UTF-8-supporting virtual terminal
on a Windows system.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/17728c8fe8f86bfe5e92cdfa4d2467279beb437f"},{"sha":"15c0645bd5d849663196417f01cafec904480b44","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"main: initialize the terminal (if any) using internal/terminal

We need to call into terminal.Init in early startup to make sure that we
either have a suitable Terminal or that we disable attempts to use virtual
terminal escape sequences.

This commit gets the terminal initialized but doesn't do much with it
after that. Subsequent commits will make more use of this.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/15c0645bd5d849663196417f01cafec904480b44"},{"sha":"d2c3403ab60e378f91ba49f70f08cbef720a5653","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command: Use the new terminal.Streams object

Here we propagate in the initialized terminal.Streams from package main,
and then onwards to backends running in CLI mode.

This also replaces our use of helper/wrappedstreams to determine whether
stdin is a terminal or a pipe. helper/wrappedstreams returns incorrect
file descriptors on Windows, causing StdinPiped to always return false on
that platform and thus causing one of the odd behaviors discussed in

Finally, this includes some wrappers around the ability to look up the
number of columns in the terminal in preparation for use elsewhere. These
wrappers deal with the fact that our unit tests typically won't populate
meta.Streams.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/d2c3403ab60e378f91ba49f70f08cbef720a5653"},{"sha":"e6a516d87e2f8a9b45102713142212296ed087bf","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"backend/local: Use terminal properties to tweak the plan output

We now require the output to accept UTF-8 and we can determine how wide
the terminal (if any) is, so here we begin to make use of that for the
"terraform plan" command.

The horizontal rule is now made of box drawing characters instead of
hyphens and fills the whole terminal width.

The paragraphs of text in the output are now also wrapped to fill the
terminal width, instead of the hard-wrapping we did before.

This is just a start down the road of making better use of the terminal
capabilities. Lots of other commands could benefit from updates like these
too.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/e6a516d87e2f8a9b45102713142212296ed087bf"},{"sha":"0c84a56700a26fa766f58052497c3731328139db","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command/format: Use box drawing chars for rules in diagnostics

We were previously using some ASCII art to create some visual divisions
between parts of the diagnostic output. Now that we are requiring a UTF-8
terminal we can print out box drawing characters instead.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/0c84a56700a26fa766f58052497c3731328139db"},{"sha":"1f1af87dead21b9fbea31cb6a0563da1efd8bd62","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command/format: Don't try to fill the last terminal column

In some terminal emulators, writing a character into the last column on a
row causes the terminal to immediately wrap to the beginning of the next
line, even if the very next character in the stream is a hard newline.
That can then lead to errant blank lines in the final output which make
it harder to navigate the visual hierarchy.

As a compromise to avoid this, we'll format our horizontal rules and
paragraphs to one column less than the terminal width. That does mean that
our horizontal rules won't _quite_ cover the whole terminal width, but
it seems like a good compromise in order to get consistent behavior across
a wider variety of terminal implementations.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/1f1af87dead21b9fbea31cb6a0563da1efd8bd62"}]

[{"sha":"e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Update package.json versions as part of build step (#20579)

Fixes issue in the new build workflow where the experimental packages do
not include "experimental" in the version string. This was because the
previous approach relied on the RELEASE_CHANNEL environment variable,

same job to build both channels. To solve, I moved the version
post-processing into the build script itself.

Longer term, I would like to remove version numbers from the source
entirely, including the package.jsons. We should use a placeholder
instead; that's mostly how it already works, since the release script
swaps out the versions before we publish to stable.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/miqdigital/react/commits/e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f"}]

[{"sha":"95eb4907805b0c8650cc1bce01844162c2c84c4a","author":{"name":"Eric Mountain","email":"7fc8ed40e23fcba13e771e5ff7913ff89a4ed835@datadoghq.com"},"message":"Use v2 capabilities in layer archives

When building images in a user-namespaced container, v3 capabilities are
stored including the root UID of the creator of the user-namespace.

This UID does not make sense outside the build environment however. If
the image is run in a non-user-namespaced runtime, or if a user-namespaced
runtime uses a different UID, the capabilities requested by the effective
bit will not be honoured by `execve(2)` due to this mismatch.

Instead, we convert v3 capabilities to v2, dropping the root UID on the
fly.

Signed-off-by: Eric Mountain <eric.mountain@datadoghq.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/moby/moby/commits/95eb4907805b0c8650cc1bce01844162c2c84c4a"},{"sha":"327daef5c19209898f11380a7bd02509d6675bcb","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"Merge pull request #41724 from EricMountain/dishonoured-capabilities

not include "experimental" in the version string. This was because the
previous approach relied on the RELEASE_CHANNEL environment variable,

post-processing into the build script itself.

[{"sha":"95eb4907805b0c8650cc1bce01844162c2c84c4a","author":{"name":"Eric Mountain","email":"7fc8ed40e23fcba13e771e5ff7913ff89a4ed835@datadoghq.com"},"message":"Use v2 capabilities in layer archives

When building images in a user-namespaced container, v3 capabilities are
stored including the root UID of the creator of the user-namespace.

This UID does not make sense outside the build environment however. If
the image is run in a non-user-namespaced runtime, or if a user-namespaced
runtime uses a different UID, the capabilities requested by the effective
bit will not be honoured by `execve(2)` due to this mismatch.

Instead, we convert v3 capabilities to v2, dropping the root UID on the
fly.

Signed-off-by: Eric Mountain <eric.mountain@datadoghq.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/meunice/moby/commits/95eb4907805b0c8650cc1bce01844162c2c84c4a"},{"sha":"327daef5c19209898f11380a7bd02509d6675bcb","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"Merge pull request #41724 from EricMountain/dishonoured-capabilities

partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

[{"sha":"e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Update package.json versions as part of build step (#20579)

Fixes issue in the new build workflow where the experimental packages do
not include "experimental" in the version string. This was because the
previous approach relied on the RELEASE_CHANNEL environment variable,
which we are no longer setting in the outer CI job, since we use the
same job to build both channels. To solve, I moved the version
post-processing into the build script itself.

Only affects the new build workflow. Old workflow is unchanged.

Longer term, I would like to remove version numbers from the source
entirely, including the package.jsons. We should use a placeholder
instead; that's mostly how it already works, since the release script
swaps out the versions before we publish to stable.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/apshada/react/commits/e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f"}]

stored including the root UID of the creator of the user-namespace.

This UID does not make sense outside the build environment however. If
the image is run in a non-user-namespaced runtime, or if a user-namespaced
runtime uses a different UID, the capabilities requested by the effective
bit will not be honoured by `execve(2)` due to this mismatch.

Instead, we convert v3 capabilities to v2, dropping the root UID on the
fly.

Signed-off-by: Eric Mountain <eric.mountain@datadoghq.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/next-stack/moby/commits/95eb4907805b0c8650cc1bce01844162c2c84c4a"},{"sha":"327daef5c19209898f11380a7bd02509d6675bcb","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"Merge pull request #41724 from EricMountain/dishonoured-capabilities

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351599571
Change-Id: I1257887e869f891aa530212ea98540b86c02dc7d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/c79cce538184f10f4b635b3c9661821afdfc6881"},{"sha":"cd7b62464304f759b14928badd3663254e264bf4","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351620042
Change-Id: I6ea89b0879013b72ad00e1d607223059a482a630","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/dabf3d8057094da094b59cfe445d1c72c0a25317"},{"sha":"706350f02372cbed8ee9dae04aabbc4a5da84760","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Implement round-robin reads.

This enables a new mode of reading from the tf.data service, where consumers read from tasks in a coordinated fashion, instead of the normal first-come first-served.

The main use case for this is coordinated bucketization for synchronous training, where we want to ensure that at each step consumers get batches with elements of similar sizes. This mitigates the inefficiency of some consumers slowly training on large examples while others quickly train on small examples, then block waiting for the slower examples to be processed.

When `consumer_index` and `num_consumers` are specified to `distribute`, each task will enforce a strict round-robin order, where its first element goes to consumer 0, second element to consumer 1, and so on. This requires that all consumers consume the same number of elements.

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"},{"sha":"9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate build tests to combined workflow (#20574)","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374"},{"sha":"b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate remaining tests to combined workflow (#20577)","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53"},{"sha":"e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Update package.json versions as part of build step (#20579)

Fixes issue in the new build workflow where the experimental packages do
not include "experimental" in the version string. This was because the
previous approach relied on the RELEASE_CHANNEL environment variable,
which we are no longer setting in the outer CI job, since we use the
same job to build both channels. To solve, I moved the version
post-processing into the build script itself.

Only affects the new build workflow. Old workflow is unchanged.

Longer term, I would like to remove version numbers from the source
entirely, including the package.jsons. We should use a placeholder
instead; that's mostly how it already works, since the release script
swaps out the versions before we publish to stable.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f"},{"sha":"fc07b070a09396e60126dd75641472f0c7504edf","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Retry with fresh otp if publish fails (#20582)

Currently, if publishing a package fails, the script crashes, and the
user must start it again from the beginning. Usually this happens
because the one-time password has timed out.

With this change, the user will be prompted for a fresh otp, and the
script will resume publishing.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/fc07b070a09396e60126dd75641472f0c7504edf"},{"sha":"5e0dfb9ee724d7dc5ada2a5423f05ab4e133d22d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Revert to last successful www sync","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/5e0dfb9ee724d7dc5ada2a5423f05ab4e133d22d"},{"sha":"d46de90c65fc9488917d84fb53b46748fd77f45f","author":{"name":"Ricky","email":"7d12b144c45a90369c62925ec4a27c43a68a93bf@gmail.com"},"message":"Add back disableSchedulerTimeoutInWorkLoop flag (#20482)

[{"sha":"e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Update package.json versions as part of build step (#20579)

Fixes issue in the new build workflow where the experimental packages do
not include "experimental" in the version string. This was because the
previous approach relied on the RELEASE_CHANNEL environment variable,
which we are no longer setting in the outer CI job, since we use the
same job to build both channels. To solve, I moved the version
post-processing into the build script itself.

Only affects the new build workflow. Old workflow is unchanged.

Longer term, I would like to remove version numbers from the source
entirely, including the package.jsons. We should use a placeholder
instead; that's mostly how it already works, since the release script
swaps out the versions before we publish to stable.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vacantthinker-forks/react/commits/e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f"},{"sha":"fc07b070a09396e60126dd75641472f0c7504edf","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Retry with fresh otp if publish fails (#20582)

Currently, if publishing a package fails, the script crashes, and the
user must start it again from the beginning. Usually this happens
because the one-time password has timed out.

With this change, the user will be prompted for a fresh otp, and the
script will resume publishing.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vacantthinker-forks/react/commits/fc07b070a09396e60126dd75641472f0c7504edf"}]

[{"sha":"95eb4907805b0c8650cc1bce01844162c2c84c4a","author":{"name":"Eric Mountain","email":"7fc8ed40e23fcba13e771e5ff7913ff89a4ed835@datadoghq.com"},"message":"Use v2 capabilities in layer archives

When building images in a user-namespaced container, v3 capabilities are
stored including the root UID of the creator of the user-namespace.

This UID does not make sense outside the build environment however. If
the image is run in a non-user-namespaced runtime, or if a user-namespaced
runtime uses a different UID, the capabilities requested by the effective
bit will not be honoured by `execve(2)` due to this mismatch.

Instead, we convert v3 capabilities to v2, dropping the root UID on the
fly.

Signed-off-by: Eric Mountain <eric.mountain@datadoghq.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vdemeester/moby/commits/95eb4907805b0c8650cc1bce01844162c2c84c4a"},{"sha":"327daef5c19209898f11380a7bd02509d6675bcb","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"Merge pull request #41724 from EricMountain/dishonoured-capabilities

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351599571
Change-Id: I1257887e869f891aa530212ea98540b86c02dc7d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/c79cce538184f10f4b635b3c9661821afdfc6881"},{"sha":"cd7b62464304f759b14928badd3663254e264bf4","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351620042
Change-Id: I6ea89b0879013b72ad00e1d607223059a482a630","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KabirKwatra/tensorflow/commits/dabf3d8057094da094b59cfe445d1c72c0a25317"},{"sha":"706350f02372cbed8ee9dae04aabbc4a5da84760","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Implement round-robin reads.

This enables a new mode of reading from the tf.data service, where consumers read from tasks in a coordinated fashion, instead of the normal first-come first-served.

The main use case for this is coordinated bucketization for synchronous training, where we want to ensure that at each step consumers get batches with elements of similar sizes. This mitigates the inefficiency of some consumers slowly training on large examples while others quickly train on small examples, then block waiting for the slower examples to be processed.

When `consumer_index` and `num_consumers` are specified to `distribute`, each task will enforce a strict round-robin order, where its first element goes to consumer 0, second element to consumer 1, and so on. This requires that all consumers consume the same number of elements.

[{"sha":"7488189446c13a65e1db888e0a4812cbfab1fe37","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command/format: Don't try to fill the last terminal column

In some terminal emulators, writing a character into the last column on a
row causes the terminal to immediately wrap to the beginning of the next
line, even if the very next character in the stream is a hard newline.
That can then lead to errant blank lines in the final output which make
it harder to navigate the visual hierarchy.

As a compromise to avoid this, we'll format our horizontal rules and
paragraphs to one column less than the terminal width. That does mean that
our horizontal rules won't _quite_ cover the whole terminal width, but
it seems like a good compromise in order to get consistent behavior across
a wider variety of terminal implementations.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/7488189446c13a65e1db888e0a4812cbfab1fe37"}]

Change-Id: I6ea89b0879013b72ad00e1d607223059a482a630","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/dabf3d8057094da094b59cfe445d1c72c0a25317"},{"sha":"706350f02372cbed8ee9dae04aabbc4a5da84760","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Implement round-robin reads.

This enables a new mode of reading from the tf.data service, where consumers read from tasks in a coordinated fashion, instead of the normal first-come first-served.

The main use case for this is coordinated bucketization for synchronous training, where we want to ensure that at each step consumers get batches with elements of similar sizes. This mitigates the inefficiency of some consumers slowly training on large examples while others quickly train on small examples, then block waiting for the slower examples to be processed.

When `consumer_index` and `num_consumers` are specified to `distribute`, each task will enforce a strict round-robin order, where its first element goes to consumer 0, second element to consumer 1, and so on. This requires that all consumers consume the same number of elements.

Change-Id: I63f1bdbfda99e20049dde682dfb65052779bf5e1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yongtang/tensorflow/commits/5400e3e63cf1d3797ea4a42687e4b4f290a4cfaa"},{"sha":"febd380da9219e08ea493b5baff765e2ef2d99d5","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Do not hang in GPU tf.math.pow if RHS is a negative int.

Before, if the RHS to tf.math.pow in the GPU kernel was negative and the inputs were int64, the GPU kernel would hang. Eigen expects the RHS to be nonnegative and will go into an infinite loop otherwise. The CPU kernel already checks this and raises an error if the RHS is negative, but we cannot easily raise errors in GPU kernels.

For the C++ jax.jit, we were able to first perform the transfer, and then inspect the result to know what the dtype and shape are.
However, for pmap, we don't necessarily know how to transfer the arguments, before having inspected the signature and retrieved the compiled executable & sharding_sec.

So for pmap, we will do explicitly the "abstractify" and the "shard_args/device_put" steps.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351599571
Change-Id: I1257887e869f891aa530212ea98540b86c02dc7d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/c79cce538184f10f4b635b3c9661821afdfc6881"},{"sha":"cd7b62464304f759b14928badd3663254e264bf4","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

[{"sha":"e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Update package.json versions as part of build step (#20579)

Fixes issue in the new build workflow where the experimental packages do
not include "experimental" in the version string. This was because the
previous approach relied on the RELEASE_CHANNEL environment variable,
which we are no longer setting in the outer CI job, since we use the
same job to build both channels. To solve, I moved the version
post-processing into the build script itself.

Only affects the new build workflow. Old workflow is unchanged.

Longer term, I would like to remove version numbers from the source
entirely, including the package.jsons. We should use a placeholder
instead; that's mostly how it already works, since the release script
swaps out the versions before we publish to stable.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tbergq/react/commits/e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f"},{"sha":"fc07b070a09396e60126dd75641472f0c7504edf","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Retry with fresh otp if publish fails (#20582)

Currently, if publishing a package fails, the script crashes, and the
user must start it again from the beginning. Usually this happens
because the one-time password has timed out.

With this change, the user will be prompted for a fresh otp, and the
script will resume publishing.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tbergq/react/commits/fc07b070a09396e60126dd75641472f0c7504edf"}]

This pass is now handled by first:
1. Decomposing control flow into the host and device portions first.
2. Moving all outside compilation ops to run in a single host parallel_execute region.

This simplifies the flow greatly and leads to simpler code path.  It will also allow the use of tf_device::LaunchOp to represent outside compilation regions.

Background:
State updates that are scheduled in a layout effect (useLayoutEffect or componentDidMount / componentDidUpdate) get processed synchronously by React before it yields to the browser to paint. This is done so that components can adjust their layout (e.g. position and size a tooltip) without any visible shifting being seen by users. This type of update is often called a "nested update" or a "cascading update".

Because they delay paint, nested updates are considered expensive and should be avoided when possible. For example, effects that do not impact layout (e.g. adding event handlers, logging impressions) can be safely deferred to the passive effect phase by using useEffect instead.

This PR updates the Profiler API to explicitly flag nested updates so they can be monitored for and avoided when possible.

Implementation:
I considered a few approaches for this.

Add a new callback (e.g. onNestedUpdateScheduled) to the Profiler that gets called when a nested updates gets scheduled.
Add an additional boolean parameter to the end of existing callbacks (e.g. wasNestedUpdate).
Update the phase param to add an additional variant: "mount", "update", or "nested-update" (new).
I think the third option makes for the best API so that's what I've implemented in this PR.

Because the Profiler API is stable, this change will need to remain behind a feature flag until v18. I've turned the feature flag on for Facebook builds though after confirming that Web Speed does not currently make use of the phase parameter.

Quirks:
One quirk about the implementation I've chosen is that errors thrown during the layout phase are also reported as nested updates. I believe this is appropriate since these errors get processed synchronously and block paint. Errors thrown during render or from within passive effects are not affected by this change.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/qianbaiduhai/react/commits/393c452e39a72932af734c7c25998b48a20698f7"},{"sha":"08986601546f69ba2c3107b472862cf2cb30d2ce","author":{"name":"Ricky","email":"7d12b144c45a90369c62925ec4a27c43a68a93bf@gmail.com"},"message":"Add version of scheduler that only swaps MessageChannel for postTask (#20206)

should be responsible for ensuring these are always correct.

during the effects refactor. The other ones have been around longer so

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351599571
Change-Id: I1257887e869f891aa530212ea98540b86c02dc7d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Nicholas282787728/tensorflow/commits/c79cce538184f10f4b635b3c9661821afdfc6881"},{"sha":"cd7b62464304f759b14928badd3663254e264bf4","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

Change-Id: I63f1bdbfda99e20049dde682dfb65052779bf5e1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/tensorflow/commits/5400e3e63cf1d3797ea4a42687e4b4f290a4cfaa"},{"sha":"febd380da9219e08ea493b5baff765e2ef2d99d5","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Do not hang in GPU tf.math.pow if RHS is a negative int.

Before, if the RHS to tf.math.pow in the GPU kernel was negative and the inputs were int64, the GPU kernel would hang. Eigen expects the RHS to be nonnegative and will go into an infinite loop otherwise. The CPU kernel already checks this and raises an error if the RHS is negative, but we cannot easily raise errors in GPU kernels.

For the C++ jax.jit, we were able to first perform the transfer, and then inspect the result to know what the dtype and shape are.
However, for pmap, we don't necessarily know how to transfer the arguments, before having inspected the signature and retrieved the compiled executable & sharding_sec.

So for pmap, we will do explicitly the "abstractify" and the "shard_args/device_put" steps.

For the C++ jax.jit, we were able to first perform the transfer, and then inspect the result to know what the dtype and shape are.
However, for pmap, we don't necessarily know how to transfer the arguments, before having inspected the signature and retrieved the compiled executable & sharding_sec.

So for pmap, we will do explicitly the "abstractify" and the "shard_args/device_put" steps.

This pass is now handled by first:
1. Decomposing control flow into the host and device portions first.
2. Moving all outside compilation ops to run in a single host parallel_execute region.

This simplifies the flow greatly and leads to simpler code path.  It will also allow the use of tf_device::LaunchOp to represent outside compilation regions.

However, because this test spins up a new daemon, not the daemon that's set up by

[{"sha":"95eb4907805b0c8650cc1bce01844162c2c84c4a","author":{"name":"Eric Mountain","email":"7fc8ed40e23fcba13e771e5ff7913ff89a4ed835@datadoghq.com"},"message":"Use v2 capabilities in layer archives

When building images in a user-namespaced container, v3 capabilities are
stored including the root UID of the creator of the user-namespace.

This UID does not make sense outside the build environment however. If
the image is run in a non-user-namespaced runtime, or if a user-namespaced
runtime uses a different UID, the capabilities requested by the effective
bit will not be honoured by `execve(2)` due to this mismatch.

Instead, we convert v3 capabilities to v2, dropping the root UID on the
fly.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351599571
Change-Id: I1257887e869f891aa530212ea98540b86c02dc7d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/c79cce538184f10f4b635b3c9661821afdfc6881"},{"sha":"cd7b62464304f759b14928badd3663254e264bf4","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

[{"sha":"95eb4907805b0c8650cc1bce01844162c2c84c4a","author":{"name":"Eric Mountain","email":"7fc8ed40e23fcba13e771e5ff7913ff89a4ed835@datadoghq.com"},"message":"Use v2 capabilities in layer archives

When building images in a user-namespaced container, v3 capabilities are
stored including the root UID of the creator of the user-namespace.

This UID does not make sense outside the build environment however. If
the image is run in a non-user-namespaced runtime, or if a user-namespaced
runtime uses a different UID, the capabilities requested by the effective
bit will not be honoured by `execve(2)` due to this mismatch.

Instead, we convert v3 capabilities to v2, dropping the root UID on the
fly.

Signed-off-by: Eric Mountain <eric.mountain@datadoghq.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/loot-king/moby/commits/95eb4907805b0c8650cc1bce01844162c2c84c4a"},{"sha":"327daef5c19209898f11380a7bd02509d6675bcb","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"Merge pull request #41724 from EricMountain/dishonoured-capabilities

Use v2 capabilities in layer archives","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/loot-king/moby/commits/327daef5c19209898f11380a7bd02509d6675bcb"}]

[{"sha":"e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Update package.json versions as part of build step (#20579)

Fixes issue in the new build workflow where the experimental packages do
not include "experimental" in the version string. This was because the
previous approach relied on the RELEASE_CHANNEL environment variable,
which we are no longer setting in the outer CI job, since we use the
same job to build both channels. To solve, I moved the version
post-processing into the build script itself.

Only affects the new build workflow. Old workflow is unchanged.

Longer term, I would like to remove version numbers from the source
entirely, including the package.jsons. We should use a placeholder
instead; that's mostly how it already works, since the release script
swaps out the versions before we publish to stable.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/r4b3rt/react/commits/e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f"},{"sha":"fc07b070a09396e60126dd75641472f0c7504edf","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Retry with fresh otp if publish fails (#20582)

Currently, if publishing a package fails, the script crashes, and the
user must start it again from the beginning. Usually this happens
because the one-time password has timed out.

With this change, the user will be prompted for a fresh otp, and the
script will resume publishing.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/r4b3rt/react/commits/fc07b070a09396e60126dd75641472f0c7504edf"}]

[{"sha":"33ef48fde1c924ac8b8901dd830600ad68ccb105","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Update package.json versions as part of build step

Fixes issue in the new build workflow where the experimental packages do
not include "experimental" in the version string. This was because the
previous approach relied on the RELEASE_CHANNEL environment variable,
which we are no longer setting in the outer CI job, since we use the
same job to build both channels. To solve, I moved the version
post-processing into the build script itself.

Only affects the new build workflow. Old workflow is unchanged.

Longer term, I would like to remove version numbers from the source
entirely, including the package.jsons. We should use a placeholder
instead; that's mostly how it already works, since the release script
swaps out the versions before we publish to stable.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/33ef48fde1c924ac8b8901dd830600ad68ccb105"}]

Change-Id: I6ea89b0879013b72ad00e1d607223059a482a630","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/testkevinbonz/tensorflow/commits/dabf3d8057094da094b59cfe445d1c72c0a25317"},{"sha":"706350f02372cbed8ee9dae04aabbc4a5da84760","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Implement round-robin reads.

This enables a new mode of reading from the tf.data service, where consumers read from tasks in a coordinated fashion, instead of the normal first-come first-served.

The main use case for this is coordinated bucketization for synchronous training, where we want to ensure that at each step consumers get batches with elements of similar sizes. This mitigates the inefficiency of some consumers slowly training on large examples while others quickly train on small examples, then block waiting for the slower examples to be processed.

When `consumer_index` and `num_consumers` are specified to `distribute`, each task will enforce a strict round-robin order, where its first element goes to consumer 0, second element to consumer 1, and so on. This requires that all consumers consume the same number of elements.

[{"sha":"95eb4907805b0c8650cc1bce01844162c2c84c4a","author":{"name":"Eric Mountain","email":"7fc8ed40e23fcba13e771e5ff7913ff89a4ed835@datadoghq.com"},"message":"Use v2 capabilities in layer archives

When building images in a user-namespaced container, v3 capabilities are
stored including the root UID of the creator of the user-namespace.

This UID does not make sense outside the build environment however. If
the image is run in a non-user-namespaced runtime, or if a user-namespaced
runtime uses a different UID, the capabilities requested by the effective
bit will not be honoured by `execve(2)` due to this mismatch.

Instead, we convert v3 capabilities to v2, dropping the root UID on the
fly.

Signed-off-by: Eric Mountain <eric.mountain@datadoghq.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rizalgowandy/moby/commits/95eb4907805b0c8650cc1bce01844162c2c84c4a"},{"sha":"327daef5c19209898f11380a7bd02509d6675bcb","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"Merge pull request #41724 from EricMountain/dishonoured-capabilities

[{"sha":"e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Update package.json versions as part of build step (#20579)

Fixes issue in the new build workflow where the experimental packages do
not include "experimental" in the version string. This was because the
previous approach relied on the RELEASE_CHANNEL environment variable,
which we are no longer setting in the outer CI job, since we use the
same job to build both channels. To solve, I moved the version
post-processing into the build script itself.

Only affects the new build workflow. Old workflow is unchanged.

Longer term, I would like to remove version numbers from the source
entirely, including the package.jsons. We should use a placeholder
instead; that's mostly how it already works, since the release script
swaps out the versions before we publish to stable.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/wadezhan/react/commits/e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f"}]

[{"sha":"95eb4907805b0c8650cc1bce01844162c2c84c4a","author":{"name":"Eric Mountain","email":"7fc8ed40e23fcba13e771e5ff7913ff89a4ed835@datadoghq.com"},"message":"Use v2 capabilities in layer archives

When building images in a user-namespaced container, v3 capabilities are
stored including the root UID of the creator of the user-namespace.

This UID does not make sense outside the build environment however. If
the image is run in a non-user-namespaced runtime, or if a user-namespaced
runtime uses a different UID, the capabilities requested by the effective
bit will not be honoured by `execve(2)` due to this mismatch.

Instead, we convert v3 capabilities to v2, dropping the root UID on the
fly.

Signed-off-by: Eric Mountain <eric.mountain@datadoghq.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JonathanSimon123/moby/commits/95eb4907805b0c8650cc1bce01844162c2c84c4a"},{"sha":"327daef5c19209898f11380a7bd02509d6675bcb","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"Merge pull request #41724 from EricMountain/dishonoured-capabilities

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351620042
Change-Id: I6ea89b0879013b72ad00e1d607223059a482a630","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/dabf3d8057094da094b59cfe445d1c72c0a25317"},{"sha":"706350f02372cbed8ee9dae04aabbc4a5da84760","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Implement round-robin reads.

This enables a new mode of reading from the tf.data service, where consumers read from tasks in a coordinated fashion, instead of the normal first-come first-served.

The main use case for this is coordinated bucketization for synchronous training, where we want to ensure that at each step consumers get batches with elements of similar sizes. This mitigates the inefficiency of some consumers slowly training on large examples while others quickly train on small examples, then block waiting for the slower examples to be processed.

When `consumer_index` and `num_consumers` are specified to `distribute`, each task will enforce a strict round-robin order, where its first element goes to consumer 0, second element to consumer 1, and so on. This requires that all consumers consume the same number of elements.

[{"sha":"46dfc313421a2f59a82343d8b812de799b3a0251","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"integration: fix TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2 not using frozen image

Commit f2f5106c92fb9399844dcb7315fe23f3612e7cea added this test to verify loading
of images that were built with user-namespaces enabled.

However, because this test spins up a new daemon, not the daemon that's set up by
the test-suite's `TestMain()` (which loads the frozen images).

As a result, the `debian:bullseye` image was pulled from Docker Hub when running
the test;

    Calling POST /v1.41/images/load?quiet=1
    Applying tar in /go/src/github.com/docker/docker/bundles/test-integration/TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2/d4d366b15997b/root/165536.165536/overlay2/3f7f9375197667acaf7bc810b34689c21f8fed9c52c6765c032497092ca023d6/diff" storage-driver=overlay
    Applied tar sha256:845f0e5159140e9dbcad00c0326c2a506fbe375aa1c229c43f082867d283149c to 3f7f9375197667acaf7bc810b34689c21f8fed9c52c6765c032497092ca023d6, size: 5922359
    Calling POST /v1.41/build?buildargs=null&cachefrom=null&cgroupparent=&cpuperiod=0&cpuquota=0&cpusetcpus=&cpusetmems=&cpushares=0&dockerfile=&labels=null&memory=0&memswap=0&networkmode=&rm=0&shmsize=0&t=capabilities%3A1.0&target=&ulimits=null&version=
    Trying to pull debian from https://registry-1.docker.io v2
    Fetching manifest from remote" digest="sha256:f169dbadc9021fc0b08e371d50a772809286a167f62a8b6ae86e4745878d283d" error="<nil>" remote="docker.io/library/debian:bullseye
    Pulling ref from V2 registry: debian:bullseye
    ...

This patch updates `TestBuildUserNamespaceValidateCapabilitiesAreV2` to load the
frozen image. `StartWithBusybox` is also changed to `Start`, because the test
is not using the busybox image, so there's no need to load it.

In a followup, we should probably add some utilities to make this easier to set up
(and to allow passing the list frozen images that we want to load, without having
to "hard-code" the image name to load).

Change-Id: I63f1bdbfda99e20049dde682dfb65052779bf5e1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/5400e3e63cf1d3797ea4a42687e4b4f290a4cfaa"},{"sha":"febd380da9219e08ea493b5baff765e2ef2d99d5","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Do not hang in GPU tf.math.pow if RHS is a negative int.

Before, if the RHS to tf.math.pow in the GPU kernel was negative and the inputs were int64, the GPU kernel would hang. Eigen expects the RHS to be nonnegative and will go into an infinite loop otherwise. The CPU kernel already checks this and raises an error if the RHS is negative, but we cannot easily raise errors in GPU kernels.

[{"sha":"e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Update package.json versions as part of build step (#20579)

Fixes issue in the new build workflow where the experimental packages do
not include "experimental" in the version string. This was because the
previous approach relied on the RELEASE_CHANNEL environment variable,
which we are no longer setting in the outer CI job, since we use the
same job to build both channels. To solve, I moved the version
post-processing into the build script itself.

Only affects the new build workflow. Old workflow is unchanged.

Longer term, I would like to remove version numbers from the source
entirely, including the package.jsons. We should use a placeholder
instead; that's mostly how it already works, since the release script
swaps out the versions before we publish to stable.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/SimenB/react/commits/e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f"},{"sha":"fc07b070a09396e60126dd75641472f0c7504edf","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Retry with fresh otp if publish fails (#20582)

Currently, if publishing a package fails, the script crashes, and the
user must start it again from the beginning. Usually this happens
because the one-time password has timed out.

With this change, the user will be prompted for a fresh otp, and the
script will resume publishing.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/SimenB/react/commits/fc07b070a09396e60126dd75641472f0c7504edf"}]

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351620042
Change-Id: I6ea89b0879013b72ad00e1d607223059a482a630","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/tensorflow/commits/dabf3d8057094da094b59cfe445d1c72c0a25317"},{"sha":"706350f02372cbed8ee9dae04aabbc4a5da84760","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Implement round-robin reads.

This enables a new mode of reading from the tf.data service, where consumers read from tasks in a coordinated fashion, instead of the normal first-come first-served.

The main use case for this is coordinated bucketization for synchronous training, where we want to ensure that at each step consumers get batches with elements of similar sizes. This mitigates the inefficiency of some consumers slowly training on large examples while others quickly train on small examples, then block waiting for the slower examples to be processed.

When `consumer_index` and `num_consumers` are specified to `distribute`, each task will enforce a strict round-robin order, where its first element goes to consumer 0, second element to consumer 1, and so on. This requires that all consumers consume the same number of elements.

Fixes issue in the new build workflow where the experimental packages do
not include "experimental" in the version string. This was because the
previous approach relied on the RELEASE_CHANNEL environment variable,

same job to build both channels. To solve, I moved the version
post-processing into the build script itself.

Only affects the new build workflow. Old workflow is unchanged.

Longer term, I would like to remove version numbers from the source
entirely, including the package.jsons. We should use a placeholder
instead; that's mostly how it already works, since the release script
